## Movement I: Moderato — The Entrance

The first movement opens with the **orchestra alone** — a quiet, somber chord progression in C minor, the melody shared between cellos and winds. The piano doesn't speak for eight full measures. When it does, it enters **softly**, almost as if unsure, with a simple arpeggiated figure that will become the movement's spine.

Here's the opening orchestral statement, **reduced to section voices** (Chapter 7 taught you to tune a voice as a whole section):

```scheme
;; Rachmaninoff Piano Concerto No. 2, Op. 18
;; Movement I: Moderato, opening 8 measures (orchestra)

(define strings-low
  (section-voice 'cello
    '((1 . 1.0) (2 . 0.6) (3 . 0.3) (4 . 0.15))))

(define winds-soft
  (section-voice 'clarinet
    '((1 . 1.0) (2 . 0.4) (3 . 0.2) (5 . 0.1))))

(define (movement-I-opening)
  (transport/tempo 80)  ; Moderato ~ 80 bpm
  
  ;; Measure 1-2: C minor chord, strings pp
  (with-voice strings-low
    (with-dynamics 'pp
      (note/place-at 0 'C3 'whole 40)
      (note/place-at 0 'Eb3 'whole 40)
      (note/place-at 0 'G3 'whole 40)))
  
  ;; Measure 3-4: winds take the melody, still pp
  (with-voice winds-soft
    (with-dynamics 'pp
      (note/place-at 8 'G4 'half 45)
      (note/place-at 10 'F4 'half 45)
      (note/place-at 12 'Eb4 'whole 42)))
  
  ;; Measure 5-6: strings answer, p
  (with-voice strings-low
    (with-dynamics 'p
      (note/place-at 16 'D3 'half 50)
      (note/place-at 18 'C3 'half 50)
      (note/place-at 20 'Bb2 'whole 48)))
  
  ;; Measure 7-8: a breath, then piano enters m.9 (next section)
  (with-voice winds-soft
    (with-dynamics 'pp
      (note/place-at 24 'C4 'whole 40))))

(movement-I-opening)
```

<!-- BUILD: wire this as a runnable example; section-voice is GAP-6 (needs full harmonic-profile tuning per Chapter 7); for now stub to (tone (midi->freq pitch) (beat-duration dur)) and mark *[needs: GAP-6]* -->

*[needs: GAP-6]* — `section-voice` here refers to the **tunable section voices** from Chapter 7 (harmonic profiles via `createPeriodicWave`). Until that's wired, the example stubs to bare tones, but the **structure** is honest: you're placing notes with dynamics, in measures, at a tempo.

The `with-dynamics` form (Chapter 13) scales velocity. The `note/place-at` positions are in **beats** — measure 1 starts at beat 0, measure 2 at beat 4 (4/4 time), and so on.

When the piano enters at measure 9, it plays a **broken chord** — an arpeggio that climbs from C to G and back. This is **ornamentation as structure** (Chapter 12 taught grace notes and arpeggios as decoration; here the arpeggio *is* the melody):

```scheme
(define piano-voice
  (section-voice 'piano
    '((1 . 1.0) (2 . 0.7) (3 . 0.4) (4 . 0.2) (5 . 0.1) (6 . 0.05))))

(define (piano-entrance)
  ;; Measure 9-10: piano enters pp, arpeggio on C minor
  (with-voice piano-voice
    (with-dynamics 'pp
      ;; eighth-note arpeggio: C - Eb - G - C - G - Eb - C
      (note/place-at 32.0 'C4 'eighth 42)
      (note/place-at 32.5 'Eb4 'eighth 42)
      (note/place-at 33.0 'G4 'eighth 44)
      (note/place-at 33.5 'C5 'eighth 46)
      (note/place-at 34.0 'G4 'eighth 44)
      (note/place-at 34.5 'Eb4 'eighth 42)
      (note/place-at 35.0 'C4 'eighth 40))))

(piano-entrance)
```

<!-- BUILD: runnable; same GAP-6 caveat on section-voice -->

*[needs: GAP-6]* — same as above. The piano's `section-voice` here includes higher harmonics (partials 4, 5, 6) to give it brightness.

[VISUAL: the piano staff showing measures 9–10, the arpeggiated C-minor figure with eighth-note beams. Each note-sprite (eighth-note glyph) bops quickly as its pitch sounds. Pressing any sprite plays that pitch on the piano voice.]

