## Layering the Orchestra: Polyphony at Scale

By measure 20, the orchestra is **fully voiced** — first violins, second violins, violas, cellos, basses, plus clarinets, oboes, horns. Each section has its own **independent line** (Chapter 9's counterpoint, scaled to a dozen voices). We don't write all twelve staves by hand; we write **motifs and distribute them**:

```scheme
(define (violins-I-motif start-beat)
  ;; First violins: a rising sequence, p
  (with-voice (section-voice 'violin '((1 . 1.0) (2 . 0.5) (3 . 0.25))))
    (with-dynamics 'p
      (note/place-at start-beat 'G4 'quarter 52)
      (note/place-at (+ start-beat 1) 'A4 'quarter 54)
      (note/place-at (+ start-beat 2) 'Bb4 'half 56))))

(define (violins-II-motif start-beat)
  ;; Second violins: a third below, same rhythm
  (with-voice (section-voice 'violin '((1 . 1.0) (2 . 0.5) (3 . 0.25))))
    (with-dynamics 'p
      (note/place-at start-beat 'Eb4 'quarter 52)
      (note/place-at (+ start-beat 1) 'F4 'quarter 54)
      (note/place-at (+ start-beat 2) 'G4 'half 56))))

(define (cellos-motif start-beat)
  ;; Cellos: a low pedal, mp
  (with-voice (section-voice 'cello '((1 . 1.0) (2 . 0.6) (3 . 0.3))))
    (with-dynamics 'mp
      (note/place-at start-beat 'C3 'whole 60))))

(define (orchestra-texture-m20)
  ;; Measure 20-23: three voices in counterpoint
  (violins-I-motif 80)
  (violins-II-motif 80)
  (cellos-motif 80)
  ;; Measure 24-27: the motifs repeat, transposed
  (violins-I-motif 96)
  (violins-II-motif 96)
  (cellos-motif 96))

(orchestra-texture-m20)
```

<!-- BUILD: runnable; GAP-6 on section-voice -->

This is **programmatic polyphony** — you define a motif as a procedure, call it with a `start-beat`, and layer multiple calls to build the texture. The violins move in parallel thirds (Chapter 6's harmony), the cellos hold a pedal tone, and the result is a **three-voice texture** that you can transpose, invert, or sequence by changing arguments.

*[needs: GAP-6]* — same section-voice dependency.

---

## Movement II: Adagio sostenuto — The Long Melody

The slow movement is **all about breath** (Chapter 13 taught rubato and expressive timing). The piano sings a **lyrical, almost vocal melody** over sustained string chords. The tempo is slow (♩ ≈ 52), and the phrasing is **loose** — Rachmaninoff marks *rubato*, meaning the performer stretches and compresses time to make the melody breathe.

Here's the opening of the Adagio theme:

```scheme
;; Movement II: Adagio sostenuto, opening theme (piano + strings)

(define (movement-II-theme)
  (transport/tempo 52)  ; Adagio ~ 52 bpm
  
  ;; Strings: a warm E-major chord, pp, sustained
  (with-voice (section-voice 'strings-warm
                '((1 . 1.0) (2 . 0.6) (3 . 0.35) (4 . 0.18))))
    (with-dynamics 'pp
      (note/place-at 0 'E3 'whole 38)
      (note/place-at 0 'G#3 'whole 38)
      (note/place-at 0 'B3 'whole 38)
      (note/place-at 0 'E4 'whole 40)))
  
  ;; Piano: the melody, p with rubato
  ;; (rubato = slight tempo flex per phrase; we approximate with beat-offset tweaks)
  (with-voice piano-voice
    (with-dynamics 'p
      ;; \"Breathe in\" — a slight delay before the first note
      (note/place-at 0.2 'B4 'quarter 50)
      ;; \"Lean on\" the second note — held slightly longer
      (note/place-at 1.1 'C#5 'quarter 52)
      (note/place-at 2.0 'D#5 'half 54)
      ;; \"Pull back\" — a ritard into the resolution
      (note/place-at 4.3 'E5 'whole 56))))

(movement-II-theme)
```

<!-- BUILD: runnable; GAP-6 on section-voice; rubato here is FAKED (manual beat-offset tweaks) — true rubato (tempo curve over time) is GAP-13 (engine needs transport tempo modulation per Chapter 13); mark *[needs: GAP-13]* -->

*[needs: GAP-6]* — section voices as above. *[needs: GAP-13]* — **true rubato** (a tempo curve that accelerates and decelerates smoothly) requires the transport to accept a **tempo modulation function** over beats, which Chapter 13 described but the engine doesn't yet wire. Here we **approximate** rubato by manually nudging `note/place-at` beat positions (0.2, 1.1, 4.3 instead of integer beats) — it's honest, but crude. The real thing will let you write:

```scheme
;; (not yet wired — this is the GAP-13 future)
(transport/tempo-curve
  '((0 . 52)    ; start at 52 bpm
    (2 . 48)    ; slow to 48 by beat 2
    (4 . 54)))  ; rise to 54 by beat 4
```

That's the gap. For now, manual offsets teach the **concept** of rubato (time is elastic, phrases breathe), even if the mechanism is by hand.

[VISUAL: the Adagio melody on a grand staff (treble for piano, bass staff below showing the string chord). The melody note-sprites (quarter and half notes) drift slowly, the halves almost languid. Dynamics marked *pp* on the strings, *p* on the piano. Tempo indication \"♩ = 52, rubato\".]

<!-- BUILD: render Adagio opening 4 bars; note-sprites idle-bopping at slow rates; press-to-sound wired -->

