## Movement III: Allegro scherzando — Virtuosity and Velocity

The finale is **fast, bright, and relentless**. Tempo ♩ = 144 (2/2 time, so ♪ = 288), and the piano part includes **sixteenth-note runs**, **thirty-second-note passages**, and **quintuplet ornaments** *[needs: GAP-1]*. The orchestra answers with **polyrhythmic cross-accents** (Chapter 10) and **tutti chords** at *fff* (Chapter 13).

Here's a fragment from the finale's main theme — the piano statement:

```scheme
;; Movement III: Allegro scherzando, main theme (piano)

(define (movement-III-theme)
  (transport/tempo 144)  ; Allegro, 2/2 time (half-note beat)
  
  ;; Piano: a driving sixteenth-note figure in C minor, f
  (with-voice piano-voice
    (with-dynamics 'f
      ;; Measure 1: sixteenths on C - D - Eb - F - G
      (note/place-at 0.00 'C5 'sixteenth 80)
      (note/place-at 0.25 'D5 'sixteenth 82)
      (note/place-at 0.50 'Eb5 'sixteenth 84)
      (note/place-at 0.75 'F5 'sixteenth 86)
      (note/place-at 1.00 'G5 'sixteenth 88)
      ;; Measure 2: a turn + leap
      (note/place-at 1.25 'F5 'sixteenth 86)
      (note/place-at 1.50 'Eb5 'sixteenth 84)
      (note/place-at 1.75 'D5 'sixteenth 82)
      (note/place-at 2.00 'C5 'quarter 90))))

(movement-III-theme)
```

<!-- BUILD: runnable; GAP-6 on section-voice; sixteenths are OK (in the allowed duration set), thirty-seconds and sixty-fourths are GAP-1 -->

The sixteenths here are **in time** (each placed at a quarter-beat offset: 0.00, 0.25, 0.50, 0.75, 1.00…). At ♩ = 144, a sixteenth is very fast — this is where the note-sprites **jitter** (Chapter's living notation: shorter durations bop faster). When thirty-seconds appear (they do in the coda), you'll mark them *[needs: GAP-1]*.

Now the orchestra **answers** with a **tutti chord** — every section at once, *fff*:

```scheme
(define (orchestra-tutti-chord beat)
  ;; All sections hit C major at fff
  (let ((chord-pitches '(C3 E3 G3 C4 E4 G4 C5)))
    ;; Strings
    (with-voice (section-voice 'strings-full
                  '((1 . 1.0) (2 . 0.7) (3 . 0.5) (4 . 0.3))))
      (with-dynamics 'fff
        (map (lambda (pitch)
               (note/place-at beat pitch 'half 100))
             chord-pitches)))
    ;; Brass (doubled for power)
    (with-voice (section-voice 'brass-bright
                  '((1 . 1.0) (2 . 0.8) (3 . 0.6) (4 . 0.4) (5 . 0.2))))
      (with-dynamics 'fff
        (map (lambda (pitch)
               (note/place-at beat pitch 'half 105))
             chord-pitches)))))

(orchestra-tutti-chord 4)  ; hits at beat 4
```

<!-- BUILD: runnable; GAP-6 on section-voice; the (map (lambda ...) ...) is core Scheme taught in Chapter 2 -->

This is **orchestration as code** (Chapter 14) — you define a chord as data (`chord-pitches`), then `map` a note-placement procedure over it, once for strings, once for brass. The result is a **doubled chord** at *fff* — twelve notes (seven pitches × two sections) sounding at once. The dynamics scale velocity to 100 and 105 (very loud).

[VISUAL: a short score showing the finale's opening — piano sixteenths on the treble staff, orchestra tutti chord (grand staff collapsed to two staves: treble + bass) at beat 4, dynamics *f* on piano, *fff* on orchestra. The sixteenth-note sprites jitter quickly; the half-note chord sprites drift more slowly. Tempo marked \"♩ = 144, Allegro scherzando\".]

