## The Cadenza: Ornamentation Unleashed

Near the end of the finale, the orchestra **drops out** and the piano plays a **cadenza** — a long, virtuosic solo passage with no accompaniment. The cadenza uses **every ornament** Chapter 12 taught: trills, tremolos, arpeggios, glissandos. Here's a simplified fragment:

```scheme
;; Finale cadenza fragment (piano solo, no orchestra)

(define (cadenza-fragment)
  (transport/tempo 144)
  
  (with-voice piano-voice
    (with-dynamics 'ff
      ;; A trill on C5, lasting a whole note
      ;; (trill = rapid alternation C5 ↔ D5)
      (trill 'C5 'D5 'whole 90)  ; *[needs: GAP-2]*
      
      ;; A descending arpeggio on C major, sixteenths
      (note/place-at 4.00 'C6 'sixteenth 88)
      (note/place-at 4.25 'G5 'sixteenth 86)
      (note/place-at 4.50 'E5 'sixteenth 84)
      (note/place-at 4.75 'C5 'sixteenth 82)
      
      ;; A glissando sweep from C5 to C6, eighth-note duration
      (glissando 'C5 'C6 'eighth 85)  ; *[needs: GAP-2]*
      
      ;; A tremolo on G4, half note (rapid reiteration)
      (tremolo 'G4 'half 80))))  ; *[needs: GAP-2]*

(cadenza-fragment)
```

<!-- BUILD: NOT runnable until GAP-2 closed; mark *[needs: GAP-2]* inline on trill/glissando/tremolo -->

*[needs: GAP-2]* — **Ornament verbs** (`trill`, `tremolo`, `glissando`) were described in Chapter 12, but the engine doesn't yet wire them as first-class verbs. The **concept** is sound: a trill schedules a rapid alternation between two pitches over a duration, a glissando schedules a pitch sweep, a tremolo schedules rapid reiteration. The **implementation** gap is that the scheduler needs to accept these as composite note-events. Until then, this example is **structurally honest** but not yet runnable. The reader knows what a trill *is* (Chapter 12 taught it), and this shows what the code *will* look like.

[VISUAL: the cadenza fragment on a single piano staff — the trill marked with a \"tr\" ornament glyph above the C5 whole note, the arpeggio shown as beamed sixteenths descending, the glissando as a wavy line connecting C5 to C6, the tremolo as slashes through the G4 half-note stem. Dynamics *ff*. Tempo \"♩ = 144\".]

<!-- BUILD: render the cadenza staff with ornament glyphs (trill · glissando · tremolo marks from the notation primitive set, §9 living notation); note-sprites + ornament sprites placed; press-to-sound stubbed to approximate sounds (trill = fast alternation, glissando = pitch sweep, tremolo = repeated note) until GAP-2 closed -->

