## Structuring the Full Concerto: The Program as Score

A full performance of Rachmaninoff 2 is **~2000 measures**. You're not going to hand-place 20,000 notes. You're going to **compose procedurally** — define themes as data, write procedures that develop and transform them, and **assemble the movements** as a program.

Here's the **skeleton** of the full concerto:

```scheme
;; Rachmaninoff Piano Concerto No. 2, Op. 18 (full program structure)

(define (rachmaninoff-concerto-no-2)
  ;; Movement I: Moderato (C minor, 4/4)
  (movement-I)
  ;; Movement II: Adagio sostenuto (E major, 4/4)
  (movement-II)
  ;; Movement III: Allegro scherzando (C minor → C major, 2/2)
  (movement-III))

(define (movement-I)
  ;; Introduction (orchestra alone, 8 bars)
  (movement-I-opening)
  ;; Piano entrance (m.9, arpeggio)
  (piano-entrance)
  ;; Exposition (themes A and B, orchestra + piano)
  (exposition-I)
  ;; Development (themes fragmented, modulated, layered)
  (development-I)
  ;; Recapitulation (themes return, now in C major)
  (recapitulation-I)
  ;; Coda (final statement, fff)
  (coda-I))

(define (movement-II)
  ;; Theme (piano melody, strings accompany)
  (movement-II-theme)
  ;; Variation 1 (theme ornamented, mf)
  (variation-II-1)
  ;; Variation 2 (theme in orchestra, piano comments)
  (variation-II-2)
  ;; Return (theme returns, pp, fading)
  (return-II))

(define (movement-III)
  ;; Theme (piano statement, f)
  (movement-III-theme)
  ;; Episode 1 (orchestra answers, fff)
  (episode-III-1)
  ;; Episode 2 (piano + orchestra, polyrhythmic)
  (episode-III-2)
  ;; Cadenza (piano solo, virtuosic)
  (cadenza-fragment)
  ;; Coda (final tutti, C major, fff → ffff)
  (coda-III))

;; Each section is a procedure that places notes on the timeline.
;; The top-level call chains them in sequence.

(rachmaninoff-concerto-no-2)
```

<!-- BUILD: this is a SKELETON (structural honesty) — each sub-procedure (exposition-I, development-I, etc.) would be defined with note/place-at calls; the skeleton is runnable if the sub-procedures are stubbed to (begin) or defined with minimal note placements; full implementation = several thousand lines; for the book, define 2–3 sections fully (done above: movement-I-opening, piano-entrance, movement-II-theme, movement-III-theme, cadenza-fragment), stub the rest with comments showing the pattern -->

This is **form as program structure** (Chapter 15). Each movement is a procedure, each section within a movement is a procedure, and the full concerto is a **single call** that chains them. The timeline is **linear** (the transport runs from beat 0 to beat N, where N is the end of the coda), and each section adds its notes to the tape.

You can **modularize further** — define themes as data structures, write `develop-theme` and `transpose-theme` and `ornament-theme` procedures, and **generate** the development and recapitulation sections from the exposition:

```scheme
(define theme-A
  '((C4 quarter) (D4 quarter) (Eb4 half)
    (D4 quarter) (C4 quarter) (Bb3 half)))

(define (play-theme theme start-beat voice dynamics)
  (with-voice voice
    (with-dynamics dynamics
      (let loop ((beats start-beat)
                 (notes theme))
        (when (not (null? notes))
          (let ((pitch (caar notes))
                (dur (cadar notes)))
            (note/place-at beats pitch dur
              (dynamics->velocity dynamics))
            (loop (+ beats (duration->beats dur))
                  (cdr notes))))))))

(define (transpose-theme theme interval)
  (map (lambda (note)
         (list (transpose-pitch (car note) interval)
               (cadr note)))
       theme))

(define (exposition-I)
  ;; Theme A in C minor, piano, p
  (play-theme theme-A 32 piano-voice 'p)
  ;; Theme A in Eb major, orchestra, mf
  (play-theme (transpose-theme theme-A 3) 48
              (section-voice 'strings-warm ...) 'mf))
```

<!-- BUILD: runnable if helper procs (dynamics->velocity, duration->beats, transpose-pitch) are defined; these are Chapter 2–6 exercises (map, lambda, arithmetic on data) — for the book, define them in a \"Helpers\" appendix or inline above the first use -->

This is **music as data transformation** (Chapter 2's lambda and lists, now at scale). The theme is a list of `(pitch duration)` pairs. `play-theme` walks the list and places notes. `transpose-theme` maps a transposition function over the list. You can **sequence**, **invert**, **retrograde**, or **augment** a theme the same way — all procedures over lists.

[VISUAL: a diagram showing `theme-A` as a list of pitch/duration pairs, an arrow labeled `transpose-theme +3`, pointing to a new list with pitches shifted up by 3 semitones. Below, a staff showing the original theme in C minor and the transposed theme in Eb major, both rendered with note-sprites.]

