## Notes and Additional Considerations from r1 draft

*The following material comes from an earlier or parallel revision draft (r1 draft). It is preserved here because content costs thought — nothing gets thrown away. Some passages restate the chapter's core ideas in a different voice; others introduce examples or angles not covered above. Read as supplemental exercises for the same discipline.*

### 1. A Sparse Concerto — Silence as Structure

The Romantic concerto fills every bar. But *sparseness* — strategic silence, long rests, isolated gestures — is a legitimate structural choice. This example builds a concerto movement where the piano enters *alone*, the orchestra responds *late*, and the dialogue is built from *space* as much as sound.

**Technique:** Use `(silence dur)` (a rest) as a first-class structural element. The program is mostly rests, punctuated by isolated chords and single notes. The form emerges from *when things don't happen*.

[VISUAL: A score with wide, empty measures; a single piano chord in bar 3, a string response in bar 7, a long silence, then a final dyad. The rests are rendered as rest glyphs (whole/half) on the staff, the silence *visible* as structure.]

```scheme
;; Sparse Concerto — movement built from silence and isolated gestures
(define (silence dur)
  ;; a rest — no sound for dur beats
  (lambda (at-beat)
    ;; schedule nothing
    #t))

(define (piano-alone pitch dur vel)
  ;; a single piano note, ADSR with long release
  (lambda (at-beat)
    (note/strike pitch dur vel)))

(define (strings-response pitches dur vel)
  ;; a soft string chord, slow attack
  (lambda (at-beat)
    (for-each
      (lambda (p)
        (note/strike p dur vel))
      pitches)))

(define (sparse-movement)
  (let ((phrases
          (list
            (silence 4.0)                     ;; 4 beats of nothing
            (piano-alone 'C4 2.0 0.6)         ;; a single middle C, held
            (silence 6.0)                     ;; 6 beats rest
            (strings-response '(E3 G3 C4) 3.0 0.4) ;; soft C-major triad, strings
            (silence 8.0)                     ;; 8 beats rest
            (piano-alone 'A3 1.5 0.5)         ;; a low A
            (silence 4.0)
            (strings-response '(F3 A3 D4) 4.0 0.35) ;; Dm, very soft
            (silence 10.0)                    ;; long final silence
            (piano-alone 'C3 6.0 0.3))))      ;; a final low C, pp, dies away
    (base/across-beats 0 phrases)))

(transport/tempo 60)
(sparse-movement)
```

<!-- BUILD: verify (silence dur) schedules no notes; render the score with rest glyphs as structural elements; confirm the movement's total duration matches the sum of all rests+notes -->

**What happened:** The concerto is 47 beats long, but only ~17 beats contain sound. The *rests are the structure*. This is a legitimate large-form technique — composers like Feldman and Part build entire works this way. The program is simple (a list of silence/note lambdas), but the *musical result* is sophisticated because the silence *means something*.

---


### 2. A Fugal Concerto — Strict Counterpoint at Scale

Most concertos are homophonic (melody + accompaniment). A *fugal concerto* is polyphonic: the piano states a subject, the orchestra answers in another voice, the subject appears in inversion, in augmentation, in stretto. This is Ch9 polyphony pushed to concerto scale.

**Technique:** Define the fugue subject as data (a list of intervals), then generate all its transformations (inversion, retrograde, augmentation, diminution) programmatically. The orchestra and piano trade entries in strict counterpoint.

[VISUAL: A four-voice fugue score. Subject in piano (treble), answer in strings (alto), subject inverted in bassoon (tenor), answer augmented in cello (bass). Each voice is color-coded; the subject's intervallic shape is the same across all four, just transformed.]

```scheme
;; Fugal Concerto — a four-voice fugue, subject + transformations
(define fugue-subject
  ;; intervals in semitones from tonic
  '(0 2 4 5 7 5 4 2 0))

(define (intervals->pitches intervals root-pitch)
  ;; convert interval list to absolute pitches
  (map (lambda (i)
         (+ (pitch->midi root-pitch) i))
       intervals))

(define (pitch->midi pitch)
  ;; map symbolic pitch to MIDI number (simplified)
  (case pitch
    ((C4) 60) ((D4) 62) ((E4) 64) ((F4) 65) ((G4) 67) ((A4) 69) ((B4) 71)
    ((C5) 72) ((D5) 74) ((E5) 76)
    ((C3) 48) ((D3) 50) ((E3) 52) ((F3) 53) ((G3) 55) ((A3) 57)
    (else 60)))

(define (invert-intervals intervals)
  ;; mirror each interval around 0
  (map (lambda (i) (- i)) intervals))

(define (augment-intervals intervals factor)
  ;; stretch each interval by factor (for augmentation, factor=2)
  (map (lambda (i) (* i factor)) intervals))

(define (retrograde-intervals intervals)
  (reverse intervals))

(define (play-voice pitches start-beat note-dur vel)
  ;; play a voice (a list of MIDI pitches) starting at start-beat
  (let loop ((ps pitches) (beat start-beat))
    (when (not (null? ps))
      (base/at-beat beat
        (lambda ()
          (note/strike (car ps) note-dur vel)))
      (loop (cdr ps) (+ beat note-dur)))))

(define (fugal-concerto)
  (let* ((root 60) ;; C4
         (subject-pitches (intervals->pitches fugue-subject root))
         (inverted (intervals->pitches (invert-intervals fugue-subject) root))
         (augmented (intervals->pitches (augment-intervals fugue-subject 2) (- root 12))) ;; down an octave
         (retro (intervals->pitches (retrograde-intervals fugue-subject) (+ root 7)))) ;; up a fifth
    ;; voice 1: subject in piano, beat 0
    (play-voice subject-pitches 0.0 0.5 0.65)
    ;; voice 2: answer (subject up a fifth) in strings, beat 4
    (play-voice (map (lambda (p) (+ p 7)) subject-pitches) 4.0 0.5 0.5)
    ;; voice 3: inversion in bassoon, beat 8
    (play-voice inverted 8.0 0.5 0.55)
    ;; voice 4: augmentation (half-speed) in cello, beat 12
    (play-voice augmented 12.0 1.0 0.6)))

(transport/tempo 96)
(fugal-concerto)
```

<!-- BUILD: confirm all four voices sound simultaneously in the second half; render a polyphonic score with each voice on its own staff; verify intervallic inversion is mathematically correct -->

**Why this is hard:** The difficulty is not the Scheme (it's map/lambda/case, all Ch2), but the *musical thinking* — understanding that a fugue subject is *data* (intervals), and all transformations are *functions on that data*. This is concerto-scale counterpoint: four independent voices, each derived from the same seed, sounding together. The program is ~40 lines; a hand-coded version would be 200+ notes.

---


### 3. A Concerto Built from World-Percussion Layers

Ch11 taught world percussion (tala, taiko, African drumming). This example builds a concerto movement where the *orchestra* is a layered percussion ensemble (taiko, djembe, tabla) and the *piano* plays a melodic line over the top. The form is sectional: intro (percussion alone), exposition (piano enters), development (polyrhythm), recapitulation (unison).

**Technique:** Define each percussion layer as a looping pattern, offset in phase. The piano melody is phrased to land on the composite downbeat of all three layers.

[VISUAL: Three percussion staves (taiko, djembe, tabla), each with a repeating ostinato pattern of different length (5, 7, 3 beats). Below, a piano staff with a melody that locks to the least-common-multiple downbeat (105 beats). The composite rhythm is a shifting polymeter.]

```scheme
;; Percussion Concerto — piano over layered world-percussion polymeter
(define (taiko-pattern)
  ;; 5-beat cycle: strong-weak-mid-weak-mid
  (list
    (beat \"taiko-low\" 1.0)
    (beat \"taiko-rim\" 0.4)
    (beat \"taiko-mid\" 0.6)
    (beat \"taiko-rim\" 0.35)
    (beat \"taiko-mid\" 0.55)))

(define (djembe-pattern)
  ;; 7-beat cycle: bass-tone-slap-tone-bass-slap-tone
  (list
    (beat \"djembe-bass\" 0.9)
    (beat \"djembe-tone\" 0.5)
    (beat \"djembe-slap\" 0.7)
    (beat \"djembe-tone\" 0.45)
    (beat \"djembe-bass\" 0.85)
    (beat \"djembe-slap\" 0.65)
    (beat \"djembe-tone\" 0.5)))

(define (tabla-pattern)
  ;; 3-beat cycle: dha-ti-na
  (list
    (beat \"tabla-dha\" 0.8)
    (beat \"tabla-ti\" 0.5)
    (beat \"tabla-na\" 0.6)))

(define (loop-pattern pattern start-beat duration beats-per-note)
  ;; loop a percussion pattern for duration beats
  (let loop ((beat start-beat) (remaining duration))
    (when (> remaining 0)
      (for-each
        (lambda (drum-hit)
          (base/at-beat beat
            (lambda () drum-hit)))
        pattern)
      (loop (+ beat (* (length pattern) beats-per-note))
            (- remaining (* (length pattern) beats-per-note))))))

(define (piano-melody-over-polymeter start-beat)
  ;; a melody that lands on beat 0, 15, 30, 45... (LCM of 5,7,3 = 105, but phrase every 15)
  (let ((phrase '(C5 D5 E5 G5 E5 D5 C5)))
    (let loop ((ps phrase) (beat start-beat))
      (when (not (null? ps))
        (base/at-beat beat
          (lambda ()
            (note/strike (car ps) 1.8 0.7)))
        (loop (cdr ps) (+ beat 2.0))))))

(define (percussion-concerto)
  ;; intro: percussion alone, 20 beats
  (loop-pattern (taiko-pattern) 0.0 20.0 1.0)
  (loop-pattern (djembe-pattern) 0.0 20.0 1.0)
  (loop-pattern (tabla-pattern) 0.0 20.0 1.0)
  ;; exposition: piano enters at beat 20, percussion continues
  (loop-pattern (taiko-pattern) 20.0 40.0 1.0)
  (loop-pattern (djembe-pattern) 20.0 40.0 1.0)
  (loop-pattern (tabla-pattern) 20.0 40.0 1.0)
  (piano-melody-over-polymeter 20.0)
  ;; recapitulation: all unison on beat 60
  (base/at-beat 60.0
    (lambda ()
      (beat \"taiko-low\" 1.0)
      (beat \"djembe-bass\" 1.0)
      (beat \"tabla-dha\" 1.0)
      (note/strike 'C4 4.0 0.9))))

(transport/tempo 120)
(percussion-concerto)
```

<!-- BUILD: confirm the three percussion patterns phase correctly; render the polymeter score with each layer on its own staff; verify the piano melody's phrasing aligns with the composite downbeat -->

**The lesson:** A concerto doesn't have to be Romantic piano + orchestra. It can be *any* solo voice over *any* ensemble. Here the ensemble is polymeter percussion, the solo is a melodic piano line, and the form is sectional. The program is 60 lines; the musical result is a full movement. This is Ch10 polyrhythm + Ch11 world percussion + Ch15 form, all composed.

---


### 4. A Data-Driven Concerto — The Score as a List

Every concerto so far has been *imperative*: \"play this note, then that note.\" This example is *declarative*: the entire concerto is a **list of events**, and a single `interpret` function walks the list and schedules everything. The program is data; the interpreter is code.

**Technique:** Define a score as a list of `(time instrument pitch dur vel)` tuples. The interpreter reads the list and calls `note/strike` for each event. To change the concerto, you edit the *data*, not the code.

[VISUAL: A table/spreadsheet-style score: columns for beat, instrument, pitch, duration, velocity. Rows are events. Below, the same events rendered on a staff. The point: the table *is* the score; the staff is just a visualization.]

```scheme
;; Data-Driven Concerto — the score is a list, the interpreter is a loop
(define concerto-score
  ;; each event: (beat instrument pitch duration velocity)
  '((0.0  piano  C4  2.0  0.7)
    (2.0  piano  E4  2.0  0.65)
    (4.0  piano  G4  2.0  0.6)
    (6.0  strings  C3  4.0  0.5)
    (6.0  strings  E3  4.0  0.5)
    (6.0  strings  G3  4.0  0.5)
    (10.0 piano  C5  1.0  0.8)
    (11.0 piano  B4  1.0  0.75)
    (12.0 piano  A4  1.0  0.7)
    (13.0 piano  G4  1.0  0.65)
    (14.0 piano  F4  2.0  0.6)
    (16.0 brass  C3  8.0  0.55)
    (16.0 brass  E3  8.0  0.55)
    (16.0 brass  G3  8.0  0.55)
    (16.0 brass  C4  8.0  0.55)
    (24.0 piano  C4  4.0  0.5)))

(define (interpret-score score)
  ;; walk the score list, schedule each event
  (for-each
    (lambda (event)
      (let ((beat (list-ref event 0))
            (instrument (list-ref event 1))
            (pitch (list-ref event 2))
            (dur (list-ref event 3))
            (vel (list-ref event 4)))
        (base/at-beat beat
          (lambda ()
            (note/strike pitch dur vel)))))
    score))

(transport/tempo 80)
(interpret-score concerto-score)
```

<!-- BUILD: verify all events in concerto-score are scheduled correctly; confirm changing a row in the score changes the sounding result without touching interpret-score -->

**Why this matters:** In a data-driven design, the *interpreter stays the same*, and *all compositional decisions live in the data*. This is how MIDI files work, how DAWs work, how music notation software works. The concerto is no longer \"code that makes sound\" — it's \"data that describes sound, plus a small interpreter.\" This separation of concerns is crucial at concerto scale: you can edit, transpose, re-orchestrate, or generate the score *without touching the playback engine*.

---


### 5. A Concerto with Nested Themes — Recursion as Form

A concerto can have *nested structure*: a theme that contains a sub-theme, which itself contains a motif, which is a recursion of the opening gesture. This example uses *recursive function calls* to mirror *recursive musical structure*.

**Technique:** Define a theme as a function that plays a motif, then calls itself with variation. The recursion bottoms out after N levels. The result: a theme that self-develops.

[VISUAL: A tree diagram. Root = main theme (4 bars). Two branches = sub-themes A and B (2 bars each). Four leaves = motifs (1 bar each). Each level is a recursive call. Below, the same structure rendered on a staff, with nested brackets showing the hierarchical phrasing.]

```scheme
;; Recursive Concerto — themes nest and develop via recursion
(define (play-motif pitch beat dur vel)
  ;; the atomic unit: a single pitch
  (base/at-beat beat
    (lambda ()
      (note/strike pitch dur vel))))

(define (recursive-theme pitch beat depth max-depth)
  ;; play a theme that recursively develops
  (when (<= depth max-depth)
    ;; play the root note
    (play-motif pitch beat 1.0 0.7)
    ;; recurse: play two sub-themes, transposed
    (recursive-theme (+ pitch 4) (+ beat 1.0) (+ depth 1) max-depth)   ;; up a major third
    (recursive-theme (+ pitch -3) (+ beat 2.0) (+ depth 1) max-depth))) ;; down a minor third

(define (recursive-concerto)
  ;; start the recursion at C4, beat 0, depth 0, max 3 levels
  (recursive-theme 60 0.0 0 3))

(transport/tempo 100)
(recursive-concerto)
```

<!-- BUILD: verify the recursion depth stops at 3; render a tree diagram showing the call structure; confirm the musical output matches the tree (each branch = a transposed sub-theme) -->

**The lesson:** Recursion is a *program structure* and a *musical structure*. The theme develops because the function calls itself with variation. At depth 0, you hear the root theme. At depth 1, you hear two sub-themes. At depth 2, four motifs. At depth 3, eight gestures. The concerto is fractal: the large structure mirrors the small structure. This is Ch15 form + structure, but the structure is *algorithmic*.

---


### 6. A Concerto with Real-Time Parameter Modulation

So far, every concerto has been *static*: notes scheduled, then played. But a concerto can be *dynamic*: tempo changes, dynamics swell, pitch bends. This example uses `transport/tempo` calls *within* the score to create accelerando and ritardando, and `note/strike` velocity ramped to create crescendo/diminuendo.

**Technique:** Schedule tempo changes as events (just like notes). Ramp velocity over a phrase by mapping a velocity curve onto a note list.

[VISUAL: A score with tempo markings (♩=60 → ♩=120 → ♩=60) above the staff, and a dynamics curve (pp → ff → pp) below. The note-sprites grow/shrink to match the dynamic, and their bop-rate speeds/slows with the tempo.]

```scheme
;; Dynamic Concerto — tempo and dynamics modulate in real-time
(define (ramp-velocity start-vel end-vel steps)
  ;; linearly interpolate velocity over steps
  (let ((delta (/ (- end-vel start-vel) (- steps 1))))
    (let loop ((i 0) (acc '()))
      (if (>= i steps)
          (reverse acc)
          (loop (+ i 1) (cons (+ start-vel (* i delta)) acc))))))

(define (play-phrase-with-dynamics pitches start-beat note-dur velocities)
  ;; play a phrase with per-note velocity
  (let loop ((ps pitches) (vs velocities) (beat start-beat))
    (when (and (not (null? ps)) (not (null? vs)))
      (base/at-beat beat
        (lambda ()
          (note/strike (car ps) note-dur (car vs))))
      (loop (cdr ps) (cdr vs) (+ beat note-dur)))))

(define (dynamic-concerto)
  ;; phrase 1: pp, slow (tempo 60)
  (transport/tempo 60)
  (let ((phrase1 '(C4 D4 E4 F4 G4 F4 E4 D4 C4))
        (vels1 (ramp-velocity 0.3 0.35 9)))
    (play-phrase-with-dynamics phrase1 0.0 1.0 vels1))
  
  ;; phrase 2: crescendo, accelerando to ff, fast (tempo 120)
  (base/at-beat 9.0
    (lambda () (transport/tempo 90)))
  (base/at-beat 12.0
    (lambda () (transport/tempo 120)))
  (let ((phrase2 '(G4 A4 B4 C5 D5 E5 F5 G5))
        (vels2 (ramp-velocity 0.4 0.9 8)))
    (play-phrase-with-dynamics phrase2 9.0 0.5 vels2))
  
  ;; phrase 3: diminuendo, ritardando to pp, slow (tempo 60)
  (base/at-beat 13.0
    (lambda () (transport/tempo 90)))
  (base/at-beat 15.0
    (lambda () (transport/tempo 60)))
  (let ((phrase3 '(G5 F5 E5 D5 C5 B4 A4 G4))
        (vels3 (ramp-velocity 0.85 0.3 8)))
    (play-phrase-with-dynamics phrase3 13.0 1.0 vels3)))

(dynamic-concerto)
```

<!-- BUILD: verify tempo changes take effect at the scheduled beat; confirm the velocity ramp is linear and covers the full pp→ff→pp range; render the score with tempo and dynamic markings -->

**Why this is hard:** The difficulty is *coordination*. You have to schedule tempo changes *before* the phrase that plays at the new tempo, and the velocity ramp has to align with the note list. This is Ch13 dynamics + rubato, but applied at concerto scale: the entire movement breathes and accelerates as a unified gesture.

---


### 7. A Concerto Built from Harmonic Rhythm

Most concertos think in *melody* (the piano line) + *accompaniment* (the orchestra). This example thinks in *harmonic rhythm*: the rate at which chords change. The piano plays arpeggios, the orchestra sustains chords, and the *structure* is the changing harmonic rhythm (slow → fast → slow).

**Technique:** Define a chord progression as a list of `(chord duration)` pairs. The orchestra plays each chord for its duration (long whole-note pads at first, then short quarter-note stabs). The piano arpeggates each chord at a rate proportional to the chord's duration.

[VISUAL: A score with whole-note chords in the strings (slow harmonic rhythm), then quarter-note chords (fast), then whole-notes again. Above, the piano plays arpeggios that speed up when the chords speed up. The harmonic rhythm *is* the form.]

```scheme
;; Harmonic-Rhythm Concerto — form driven by chord-change rate
(define (chord->pitches chord)
  ;; map chord symbol to pitch list
  (case chord
    ((Cmaj) '(60 64 67))   ;; C E G
    ((Fmaj) '(65 69 72))   ;; F A C
    ((Gmaj) '(67 71 74))   ;; G B D
    ((Am)   '(69 72 76))   ;; A C E
    ((Dm)   '(62 65 69))   ;; D F A
    (else '(60 64 67))))

(define (play-chord-pad pitches beat dur vel)
  ;; orchestra: sustain the chord for dur beats
  (for-each
    (lambda (p)
      (base/at-beat beat
        (lambda ()
          (note/strike p dur vel))))
    pitches))

(define (play-arpeggio pitches beat total-dur note-dur vel)
  ;; piano: arpeggiate the chord over total-dur
  (let loop ((ps pitches) (b beat))
    (when (and (not (null? ps)) (< b (+ beat total-dur)))
      (base/at-beat b
        (lambda ()
          (note/strike (car ps) note-dur vel)))
      (loop (cdr ps) (+ b note-dur)))))

(define (interpret-harmonic-rhythm progression)
  ;; progression: list of (chord-symbol duration)
  (let loop ((prog progression) (beat 0.0))
    (when (not (null? prog))
      (let* ((entry (car prog))
             (chord-sym (car entry))
             (dur (cadr entry))
             (pitches (chord->pitches chord-sym)))
        ;; orchestra: pad
        (play-chord-pad pitches beat dur 0.5)
        ;; piano: arpeggiate, note-dur inversely proportional to chord duration
        (play-arpeggio pitches beat dur (/ dur 4.0) 0.65)
        (loop (cdr prog) (+ beat dur))))))

(define (harmonic-rhythm-concerto)
  (let ((progression
          '((Cmaj 4.0)   ;; slow: whole-note chords
            (Fmaj 4.0)
            (Gmaj 4.0)
            (Cmaj 2.0)   ;; faster: half-notes
            (Am 2.0)
            (Dm 2.0)
            (Gmaj 2.0)
            (Cmaj 1.0)   ;; fast: quarter-notes
            (Fmaj 1.0)
            (Gmaj 1.0)
            (Cmaj 1.0)
            (Cmaj 8.0)))) ;; slow again: long final chord
    (interpret-harmonic-rhythm progression)))

(transport/tempo 80)
(harmonic-rhythm-concerto)
```

<!-- BUILD: verify the arpeggio note-duration scales inversely with chord duration; render the harmonic-rhythm score with chord durations marked; confirm the fast section (1.0-beat chords) sounds busier than the slow section (4.0-beat) -->

**The lesson:** Harmonic rhythm — the rate at which chords change — is a *structural parameter*. A slow harmonic rhythm feels stable, spacious. A fast harmonic rhythm feels urgent, driving. By varying harmonic rhythm, you control the *pacing* of the concerto without changing tempo or melody. This is Ch6 harmony + Ch15 form, but the form is *entirely in the chord durations*.

---


### 8. A Concerto with Stretto — Overlapping Imitative Entries

Stretto is a fugal technique where the subject enters *before the previous statement finishes*, creating overlapping imitation. This example builds a concerto movement where a theme enters in the piano, then in the strings one beat later, then in the brass one beat after that — all overlapping, creating a dense, imitative texture.

**Technique:** Schedule the same theme at staggered beats, each in a different voice/register.

[VISUAL: A score with three staves (piano, strings, brass). The same melodic shape appears in all three, but offset by one beat each. The entries overlap, creating a dense canonic texture.]

```scheme
;; Stretto Concerto — overlapping imitative entries
(define (theme-melody pitches)
  ;; the subject: a list of pitches
  pitches)

(define (play-theme-in-voice pitches start-beat note-dur vel voice-offset)
  ;; play the theme, transposed by voice-offset semitones
  (let loop ((ps pitches) (beat start-beat))
    (when (not (null? ps))
      (base/at-beat beat
        (lambda ()
          (note/strike (+ (car ps) voice-offset) note-dur vel)))
      (loop (cdr ps) (+ beat note-dur)))))

(define (stretto-concerto)
  (let ((subject '(60 62 64 65 67 65 64 62 60))) ;; C D E F G F E D C
    ;; voice 1: piano, starts at beat 0
    (play-theme-in-voice subject 0.0 0.5 0.7 0)
    ;; voice 2: strings, starts at beat 1 (before voice 1 finishes)
    (play-theme-in-voice subject 1.0 0.5 0.6 -12) ;; down an octave
    ;; voice 3: brass, starts at beat 2 (before voices 1 & 2 finish)
    (play-theme-in-voice subject 2.0 0.5 0.65 7))) ;; up a fifth

(transport/tempo 120)
(stretto-concerto)
```

<!-- BUILD: confirm all three voices overlap; render the stretto score showing the three staggered entries; verify the subject's intervallic shape is preserved in all voices (just transposed) -->

**The lesson:** Stretto compresses time. Instead of waiting for a theme to finish before the next voice enters, you *overlap* the entries. This creates urgency, density, inevitability. It's a fugal technique, but it works in any polyphonic context. This is Ch9 polyphony + Ch2 lists + Ch15 form — the form is *contrapuntal compression*.

---


### 9. A Concerto with Cross-Rhythm Hemiola

Hemiola is a rhythmic device where a 3-beat pattern is superimposed on a 2-beat meter (or vice versa), creating a momentary cross-rhythm. This example builds a concerto movement in 3/4 where the piano plays a 2-beat pattern, creating hemiola against the orchestra's 3-beat meter.

**Technique:** The orchestra plays in 3/4 (dotted-half chords). The piano plays in 2/4 (half-note patterns). The two meters phase in and out of alignment.

[VISUAL: Two staves. Strings: 3/4 meter, dotted-half chords (3 beats per chord). Piano: 2/4 meter, half-note patterns (2 beats per pattern). The barlines don't align — the hemiola is visible as a metric conflict.]

```scheme
;; Hemiola Concerto — 3-beat meter vs 2-beat pattern
(define (play-waltz-bass beat-start num-bars)
  ;; orchestra: 3/4 waltz bass (strong-weak-weak)
  (let loop ((bar 0) (beat beat-start))
    (when (< bar num-bars)
      (base/at-beat beat
        (lambda ()
          (note/strike 'C3 0.8 0.7)))        ;; strong
      (base/at-beat (+ beat 1.0)
        (lambda ()
          (note/strike 'G3 0.6 0.5)))        ;; weak
      (base/at-beat (+ beat 2.0)
        (lambda ()
          (note/strike 'G3 0.6 0.5)))        ;; weak
      (loop (+ bar 1) (+ beat 3.0)))))

(define (play-hemiola-piano beat-start num-cycles)
  ;; piano: 2-beat pattern (conflicts with 3/4 meter)
  (let loop ((cycle 0) (beat beat-start))
    (when (< cycle num-cycles)
      (base/at-beat beat
        (lambda ()
          (note/strike 'E4 1.0 0.65)))
      (base/at-beat (+ beat 1.0)
        (lambda ()
          (note/strike 'C4 1.0 0.65)))
      (loop (+ cycle 1) (+ beat 2.0)))))

(define (hemiola-concerto)
  ;; 8 bars of 3/4 waltz bass
  (play-waltz-bass 0.0 8)
  ;; 12 cycles of 2-beat hemiola piano (12*2=24 beats = 8 bars of 3/4)
  (play-hemiola-piano 0.0 12))

(transport/tempo 120)
(hemiola-concerto)
```

<!-- BUILD: verify the piano's 2-beat pattern phases against the orchestra's 3-beat meter; render the score with dual time signatures (3/4 for strings, 2/4 implied for piano); confirm the hemiola resolves at beat 24 (LCM of 2 and 3) -->

**The lesson:** Hemiola is a *metric conflict*. The two parts are playing in different meters, but they resolve at the LCM (least common multiple) of the two cycle lengths. It creates tension and release, a hallmark of Romantic concerto writing. This is Ch10 polyrhythm, but applied vertically (simultaneous conflicting meters) instead of horizontally (offsetting a single meter).

---


### 10. A Concerto with a Walking Bassline

Jazz concertos often feature a walking bassline: a steady quarter-note bass part that outlines the chord progression, independent of the melody. This example builds a concerto movement where the piano plays a bebop melody, the strings walk a bassline, and the brass punctuate with offbeat chords.

**Technique:** Generate a walking bassline by picking chord tones and passing tones on every beat. The bassline is algorithmic, but it sounds hand-composed.

[VISUAL: Three staves. Bass (strings): walking quarter-notes, every beat filled. Piano: syncopated bebop melody, lots of rests. Brass: offbeat chords on the \"and\" of beats 2 and 4. The walking bass ties it all together.]

```scheme
;; Walking-Bass Concerto — jazz-influenced piano + walking bassline
(define (chord->root chord)
  (case chord
    ((Cmaj7) 48)  ;; C2
    ((Dm7)   50)  ;; D2
    ((G7)    55)  ;; G2
    ((Am7)   57)  ;; A2
    (else 48)))

(define (generate-walking-bass chord num-beats)
  ;; generate a walking bassline for num-beats over chord
  ;; strategy: chord root, fifth, root, passing tone
  (let* ((root (chord->root chord))
         (fifth (+ root 7))
         (passing (+ root 2))) ;; a passing tone (major 2nd above root)
    (case num-beats
      ((4) (list root fifth root passing))
      ((2) (list root fifth))
      (else (list root)))))

(define (play-walking-bass progression start-beat)
  ;; progression: list of (chord duration-in-beats)
  (let loop ((prog progression) (beat start-beat))
    (when (not (null? prog))
      (let* ((entry (car prog))
             (chord (car entry))
             (dur (cadr entry))
             (bass-notes (generate-walking-bass chord dur)))
        (let inner ((notes bass-notes) (b beat))
          (when (not (null? notes))
            (base/at-beat b
              (lambda ()
                (note/strike (car notes) 0.9 0.6)))
            (inner (cdr notes) (+ b 1.0))))
        (loop (cdr prog) (+ beat dur))))))

(define (play-bebop-melody start-beat)
  ;; a syncopated bebop melody
  (let ((phrase '((0.5 67) (1.5 69) (2.0 71) (3.5 72) (4.0 74) (5.5 72) (6.0 71) (7.0 67))))
    (for-each
      (lambda (note-event)
        (let ((offset (car note-event))
              (pitch (cadr note-event)))
          (base/at-beat (+ start-beat offset)
            (lambda ()
              (note/strike pitch 0.4 0.75)))))
      phrase)))

(define (walking-bass-concerto)
  (let ((progression '((Cmaj7 4) (Dm7 4) (G7 4) (Cmaj7 4))))
    (play-walking-bass progression 0.0)
    (play-bebop-melody 0.0)))

(transport/tempo 180)
(walking-bass-concerto)
```

<!-- BUILD: verify the walking bassline lands on every beat; confirm the bebop melody is syncopated (notes on offbeats); render the score with the walking bass on a separate staff, showing the steady quarter-note motion -->

**The lesson:** A walking bassline is *constant motion*. It fills every beat, outlines the harmony, and propels the piece forward. The melody can be sparse and syncopated because the bass is always there, holding down the time and the chords. This is Ch6 harmony + Ch5 rhythm + Ch8 jazz timbre, all integrated.

---


### 11. A Concerto with Metric Modulation

Metric modulation is a tempo technique where the beat subdivides (or multiplies) to create a new tempo that's mathematically related to the old tempo. Example: if ♩=120, and you modulate so that the old eighth-note becomes the new quarter-note, the new tempo is ♩=240. This example builds a concerto movement that modulates from ♩=60 to ♩=90 to ♩=180 via metric modulation.

**Technique:** Schedule tempo changes where the new tempo is a multiple of the old beat subdivision.

[VISUAL: A score with tempo markings: ♩=60 (quarter=60). At bar 4, a marking \"♪ of previous bar = ♩ of this bar\" and ♩=90. At bar 8, \"♪ of previous bar = ♩ of this bar\" and ♩=135. The tempo accelerates by metric relationship, not arbitrarily.]

```scheme
;; Metric-Modulation Concerto — tempo changes via beat subdivision
(define (play-phrase-at-tempo pitches start-beat note-dur vel)
  (let loop ((ps pitches) (beat start-beat))
    (when (not (null? ps))
      (base/at-beat beat
        (lambda ()
          (note/strike (car ps) note-dur vel)))
      (loop (cdr ps) (+ beat note-dur)))))

(define (metric-modulation-concerto)
  ;; section 1: tempo 60, quarter-notes
  (transport/tempo 60)
  (play-phrase-at-tempo '(C4 D4 E4 F4) 0.0 1.0 0.7)
  
  ;; modulation 1: old eighth = new quarter, so new tempo = 60 * 1.5 = 90
  (base/at-beat 4.0
    (lambda () (transport/tempo 90)))
  (play-phrase-at-tempo '(G4 A4 B4 C5) 4.0 1.0 0.75)
  
  ;; modulation 2: old eighth = new quarter, so new tempo = 90 * 1.5 = 135
  (base/at-beat 8.0
    (lambda () (transport/tempo 135)))
  (play-phrase-at-tempo '(C5 B4 A4 G4) 8.0 1.0 0.8)
  
  ;; modulation 3: old eighth = new quarter, so new tempo = 135 * 1.5 = 202.5
  (base/at-beat 12.0
    (lambda () (transport/tempo 202)))
  (play-phrase-at-tempo '(F4 E4 D4 C4) 12.0 1.0 0.85))

(metric-modulation-concerto)
```

<!-- BUILD: verify each tempo change is a 1.5× multiple of the previous; render the score with metric-modulation markings; confirm the perceived acceleration matches the mathematical relationship -->

**The lesson:** Metric modulation makes tempo changes feel *inevitable* rather than arbitrary. The new tempo is not \"faster\" — it's \"the old subdivision.\" This technique (pioneered by Elliott Carter) is common in 20th-century concertos. The program is simple (three tempo changes), but the musical result is sophisticated because the *relationship* between tempos is rigorous.

---


### 12. A Concerto Built from a Twelve-Tone Row

A twelve-tone concerto uses all twelve pitches of the chromatic scale in a fixed order (the \"row\"), with no pitch repeated until all twelve have sounded. This example builds a concerto movement from a twelve-tone row and its transformations (retrograde, inversion, retrograde-inversion).

**Technique:** Define the row as a list of MIDI pitches. Generate transformations algorithmically. The entire concerto is built from this one row.

[VISUAL: A table showing the prime row (P0), its retrograde (R0), its inversion (I0), and its retrograde-inversion (RI0). Below, a score showing a phrase built from P0, then R0, then I0, then RI0 — all the same twelve pitches, just reordered.]

```scheme
;; Twelve-Tone Concerto — row + transformations
(define twelve-tone-row
  ;; a row: all 12 chromatic pitches, no repeats
  '(60 64 67 63 70 66 69 61 65 68 62 71)) ;; C E G Eb Bb F# A C# F Ab D B

(define (retrograde row)
  (reverse row))

(define (invert row)
  ;; inversion: mirror each interval around the first pitch
  (let ((first (car row)))
    (map (lambda (p)
           (- (* 2 first) p))
         row)))

(define (retrograde-inversion row)
  (reverse (invert row)))

(define (play-row row start-beat note-dur vel)
  (let loop ((ps row) (beat start-beat))
    (when (not (null? ps))
      (base/at-beat beat
        (lambda ()
          (note/strike (car ps) note-dur vel)))
      (loop (cdr ps) (+ beat note-dur)))))

(define (twelve-tone-concerto)
  ;; prime row
  (play-row twelve-tone-row 0.0 0.5 0.7)
  ;; retrograde
  (play-row (retrograde twelve-tone-row) 6.0 0.5 0.65)
  ;; inversion
  (play-row (invert twelve-tone-row) 12.0 0.5 0.7)
  ;; retrograde-inversion
  (play-row (retrograde-inversion twelve-tone-row) 18.0 0.5 0.65))

(transport/tempo 100)
(twelve-tone-concerto)
```

<!-- BUILD: verify the row contains all 12 unique pitch-classes; confirm inversion mirrors intervals correctly; render a score showing P0, R0, I0, RI0 as four phrases -->

**The lesson:** Twelve-tone technique is *data transformation*. The row is data, and all transformations (retrograde, inversion, transposition) are functions on that data. The concerto is built from one twelve-pitch seed, but it sounds varied because the transformations reorder the pitches. This is Ch2 lists + Ch4 sequence + Ch15 form, but the form is *serialist*.

---


### 13. A Concerto with a Cadenza — Unmetered Solo

A cadenza is a solo passage, traditionally unmetered (not bound to the beat), where the soloist improvises (or plays a written-out \"improvisation\"). This example builds a concerto movement with a metered orchestral section, then a cadenza where the piano plays freely (no transport/tempo), then the orchestra re-enters.

**Technique:** The cadenza uses *absolute time* (in seconds, not beats). The rest of the concerto uses *musical time* (beats).

[VISUAL: A score. Bars 1–8: orchestra + piano, metered. Bar 9: a fermata (hold), then the word \"cadenza\" and a bracket over 4 bars of piano solo with no barlines. Bar 13: \"a tempo\" and the orchestra re-enters, metered again.]

```scheme
;; Cadenza Concerto — metered section, unmetered cadenza, return to meter
(define (play-metered-section)
  ;; orchestra + piano, in tempo
  (let ((orch-chords '((0.0 (C3 E3 G3)) (2.0 (F3 A3 C4)) (4.0 (G3 B3 D4)) (6.0 (C3 E3 G3))))
        (piano-melody '((0.5 C5) (1.0 D5) (1.5 E5) (2.5 F5) (3.0 G5) (3.5 A5) (4.5 B5) (5.0 C6))))
    ;; orchestra
    (for-each
      (lambda (chord-event)
        (let ((beat (car chord-event))
              (pitches (cadr chord-event)))
          (for-each
            (lambda (p)
              (base/at-beat beat
                (lambda ()
                  (note/strike p 1.8 0.5))))
            pitches)))
      orch-chords)
    ;; piano
    (for-each
      (lambda (note-event)
        (let ((beat (car note-event))
              (pitch (cadr note-event)))
          (base/at-beat beat
            (lambda ()
              (note/strike pitch 0.4 0.7)))))
      piano-melody)))

(define (play-cadenza-unmetered)
  ;; piano solo, unmetered (uses tone with duration in seconds, not beats)
  ;; *[needs: GAP — unmetered scheduling; for now, fake it with slow tempo + long beats]*
  (transport/tempo 30) ;; very slow, so \"beats\" feel like free time
  (let ((cadenza-pitches '(72 74 76 77 79 81 83 84 83 81 79 77 76 74 72)))
    (let loop ((ps cadenza-pitches) (beat 8.0)) ;; start after metered section
      (when (not (null? ps))
        (base/at-beat beat
          (lambda ()
            (note/strike (car ps) 1.5 0.8)))
        (loop (cdr ps) (+ beat 0.8)))))) ;; irregular spacing

(define (play-return-to-tempo)
  ;; orchestra re-enters, back in tempo
  (transport/tempo 100)
  (base/at-beat 20.0
    (lambda ()
      (for-each
        (lambda (p)
          (note/strike p 4.0 0.6))
        '(C3 E3 G3 C4)))))

(define (cadenza-concerto)
  (play-metered-section)
  (play-cadenza-unmetered)
  (play-return-to-tempo))

(transport/tempo 100)
(cadenza-concerto)
```

<!-- BUILD: verify the metered section uses transport/tempo 100; the cadenza section uses tempo 30 (to fake unmetered time); the return uses tempo 100 again; mark *[needs: GAP — true unmetered scheduling]* in the prose -->

**Why this is awkward:** True unmetered time (where the soloist is not locked to a beat grid) is *[needs: GAP — unmetered scheduling]*. The example above fakes it by slowing the tempo way down and using irregular beat offsets. But the *idea* is sound: a cadenza is a *mode switch* from metered to unmetered time. This is Ch13 rubato pushed to the extreme — infinite rubato = no meter.

---


### 14. A Concerto with Layered Dynamics — pp/mf/ff Simultaneously

Most dynamics are *global* (the whole ensemble gets louder or softer together). But in a concerto, you can have *layered dynamics*: the piano plays ff while the strings play pp. This example builds a concerto movement where three layers (piano, strings, brass) each have independent dynamic curves.

**Technique:** Each voice gets its own velocity ramp, scheduled independently.

[VISUAL: Three staves with independent dynamic markings. Piano: pp → ff. Strings: mf throughout. Brass: ff → pp. The three curves are simultaneous but independent.]

```scheme
;; Layered-Dynamics Concerto — independent dynamic curves per voice
(define (play-voice-with-dynamic-curve pitches start-beat note-dur vels)
  ;; play a voice with per-note velocity from vels list
  (let loop ((ps pitches) (vs vels) (beat start-beat))
    (when (and (not (null? ps)) (not (null? vs)))
      (base/at-beat beat
        (lambda ()
          (note/strike (car ps) note-dur (car vs))))
      (loop (cdr ps) (cdr vs) (+ beat note-dur)))))

(define (layered-dynamics-concerto)
  (let ((phrase-length 8)
        (piano-pitches '(60 62 64 65 67 69 71 72))
        (strings-pitches '(48 50 52 53 55 57 59 60))
        (brass-pitches '(55 57 59 60 62 64 65 67)))
    ;; piano: pp → ff (0.3 → 0.95)
    (let ((piano-vels (ramp-velocity 0.3 0.95 phrase-length)))
      (play-voice-with-dynamic-curve piano-pitches 0.0 1.0 piano-vels))
    ;; strings: mf throughout (0.55)
    (let ((strings-vels (make-list phrase-length 0.55)))
      (play-voice-with-dynamic-curve strings-pitches 0.0 1.0 strings-vels))
    ;; brass: ff → pp (0.9 → 0.35)
    (let ((brass-vels (ramp-velocity 0.9 0.35 phrase-length)))
      (play-voice-with-dynamic-curve brass-pitches 0.0 1.0 brass-vels))))

(define (make-list n val)
  ;; helper: make a list of n copies of val
  (if (<= n 0)
      '()
      (cons val (make-list (- n 1) val))))

(transport/tempo 90)
(layered-dynamics-concerto)
```

<!-- BUILD: confirm the three voices have independent velocity curves; render the score with three dynamic markings (one per staff); verify piano crescendos, brass diminuendos, strings stay constant -->

**The lesson:** Layered dynamics create *textural depth*. The piano can surge forward while the orchestra recedes, or vice versa. This is Ch13 dynamics, but applied *per-voice* rather than globally. It's a concerto-specific technique: the soloist and ensemble are independent dynamic agents.

---


### 15. A Concerto with Polymeter — 5/4 Piano vs 4/4 Orchestra

We've done polyrhythm (Ch10) and hemiola (earlier in this chapter). This example goes further: *true polymeter*, where the piano is in 5/4 and the orchestra is in 4/4, and they never resolve (no LCM cadence).

**Technique:** Schedule the piano on a 5-beat cycle, the orchestra on a 4-beat cycle. Let them run in parallel for 20 beats (4 piano bars, 5 orchestra bars). The barlines never align.

[VISUAL: Two grand staves. Top (piano): 5/4 time signature, 5 beats per bar. Bottom (orchestra): 4/4 time signature, 4 beats per bar. The barlines are staggered — the two meters are simultaneous but independent.]

```scheme
;; Polymeter Concerto — 5/4 vs 4/4, no resolution
(define (play-piano-5-4 num-bars)
  ;; piano: 5/4 meter (5 beats per bar)
  (let loop ((bar 0) (beat 0.0))
    (when (< bar num-bars)
      ;; a 5-beat pattern: strong-weak-mid-weak-weak
      (base/at-beat beat
        (lambda () (note/strike 'C5 0.8 0.75)))
      (base/at-beat (+ beat 1.0)
        (lambda () (note/strike 'E5 0.6 0.55)))
      (base/at-beat (+ beat 2.0)
        (lambda () (note/strike 'G5 0.7 0.6)))
      (base/at-beat (+ beat 3.0)
        (lambda () (note/strike 'E5 0.6 0.55)))
      (base/at-beat (+ beat 4.0)
        (lambda () (note/strike 'C5 0.6 0.5)))
      (loop (+ bar 1) (+ beat 5.0)))))

(define (play-orchestra-4-4 num-bars)
  ;; orchestra: 4/4 meter (4 beats per bar)
  (let loop ((bar 0) (beat 0.0))
    (when (< bar num-bars)
      ;; a 4-beat pattern: bass on 1, chords on 2 and 4
      (base/at-beat beat
        (lambda () (note/strike 'C3 0.9 0.7)))
      (base/at-beat (+ beat 1.0)
        (lambda ()
          (for-each
            (lambda (p) (note/strike p 0.8 0.5))
            '(E3 G3 C4))))
      (base/at-beat (+ beat 3.0)
        (lambda ()
          (for-each
            (lambda (p) (note/strike p 0.8 0.5))
            '(E3 G3 C4))))
      (loop (+ bar 1) (+ beat 4.0)))))

(define (polymeter-concerto)
  ;; 4 bars of piano 5/4 = 20 beats
  ;; 5 bars of orchestra 4/4 = 20 beats
  ;; they run in parallel, barlines never align
  (play-piano-5-4 4)
  (play-orchestra-4-4 5))

(transport/tempo 120)
(polymeter-concerto)
```

<!-- BUILD: verify the piano plays 4 bars of 5/4 and the orchestra plays 5 bars of 4/4 simultaneously; render the polymeter score with dual time signatures; confirm the two parts end at the same total beat (20) but their internal barlines never align -->

**The lesson:** Polymeter is *metric independence*. The two parts are not in different subdivisions of the same beat (that's polyrhythm) — they're in *different meters entirely*. It creates a floating, unresolved texture. This is Ch10 polyrhythm + Ch5 meter, pushed to the extreme. It's disorienting, which is the point.

---


### 16. A Concerto with a Ground Bass — Variations Over a Repeating Bass

A ground bass (basso ostinato) is a repeating bassline over which variations are built. Baroque concertos (Vivaldi, Bach) often use this technique. This example builds a concerto movement with an 8-beat ground bass that repeats 8 times, while the piano plays increasingly elaborate variations over the top.

**Technique:** Loop the bassline. For each iteration, the piano plays a different variation (melody, then arpeggios, then trills, then chords).

[VISUAL: A score with the bass staff showing the same 8-note pattern repeating 8 times. Above, the piano staff shows 8 different variations: simple melody, then sixteenth-note runs, then arpeggios, then full chords. The bass is the constant; the piano is the variable.]

```scheme
;; Ground-Bass Concerto — variations over repeating bassline
(define ground-bass
  ;; an 8-beat bassline (MIDI pitches)
  '(48 50 52 53 55 53 52 50)) ;; C D E F G F E D

(define (play-ground-bass num-iterations)
  ;; loop the bassline num-iterations times
  (let loop ((i 0) (beat 0.0))
    (when (< i num-iterations)
      (let inner ((ps ground-bass) (b beat))
        (when (not (null? ps))
          (base/at-beat b
            (lambda ()
              (note/strike (car ps) 0.9 0.6)))
          (inner (cdr ps) (+ b 1.0))))
      (loop (+ i 1) (+ beat 8.0)))))

(define (variation-1 start-beat)
  ;; simple melody
  (for-each
    (lambda (note-event)
      (let ((offset (car note-event))
            (pitch (cadr note-event)))
        (base/at-beat (+ start-beat offset)
          (lambda ()
            (note/strike pitch 0.8 0.7)))))
    '((0.0 60) (1.0 62) (2.0 64) (3.0 65) (4.0 67) (5.0 65) (6.0 64) (7.0 62))))

(define (variation-2 start-beat)
  ;; sixteenth-note run
  (let ((run '(60 62 64 65 67 69 71 72 74 72 71 69 67 65 64 62)))
    (let loop ((ps run) (beat start-beat))
      (when (not (null? ps))
        (base/at-beat beat
          (lambda ()
            (note/strike (car ps) 0.3 0.65)))
        (loop (cdr ps) (+ beat 0.5))))))

(define (variation-3 start-beat)
  ;; arpeggios
  (let ((arp1 '(60 64 67 72))
        (arp2 '(62 65 69 74)))
    (let loop ((ps arp1) (beat start-beat))
      (when (not (null? ps))
        (base/at-beat beat
          (lambda ()
            (note/strike (car ps) 0.4 0.7)))
        (loop (cdr ps) (+ beat 1.0))))
    (let loop ((ps arp2) (beat (+ start-beat 4.0)))
      (when (not (null? ps))
        (base/at-beat beat
          (lambda ()
            (note/strike (car ps) 0.4 0.7)))
        (loop (cdr ps) (+ beat 1.0))))))

(define (variation-4 start-beat)
  ;; full chords
  (for-each
    (lambda (chord-event)
      (let ((offset (car chord-event))
            (pitches (cadr chord-event)))
        (for-each
          (lambda (p)
            (base/at-beat (+ start-beat offset)
              (lambda ()
                (note/strike p 1.8 0.75))))
          pitches)))
    '((0.0 (60 64 67)) (2.0 (62 65 69)) (4.0 (64 67 71)) (6.0 (65 69 72)))))

(define (ground-bass-concerto)
  ;; ground bass loops 8 times
  (play-ground-bass 8)
  ;; variations over each iteration
  (variation-1 0.0)    ;; iteration 1
  (variation-1 8.0)    ;; iteration 2
  (variation-2 16.0)   ;; iteration 3
  (variation-2 24.0)   ;; iteration 4
  (variation-3 32.0)   ;; iteration 5
  (variation-3 40.0)   ;; iteration 6
  (variation-4 48.0)   ;; iteration 7
  (variation-4 56.0))  ;; iteration 8

(transport/tempo 100)
(ground-bass-concerto)
```

<!-- BUILD: confirm the bassline repeats exactly 8 times; verify each variation starts at the correct beat; render the score with the ground bass on a separate staff, showing the repeating pattern and the varied piano parts above -->

**The lesson:** A ground bass is *thematic constancy + surface variety*. The bass is the anchor; the variations are the interest. This is Ch4 variation + Ch15 form, but the form is *additive* (each variation is independent, but they all share the same harmonic foundation). This is a Baroque technique, but it works in any era.

---


### 17. A Concerto with Tempo Acceleration to Presto

Many Romantic concertos end with a furious *presto* finale — a gradual acceleration from moderate tempo to breakneck speed. This example builds a concerto movement that starts at ♩=80 and accelerates to ♩=200 over 32 beats, with the piano playing faster note-values as the tempo rises.

**Technique:** Schedule tempo changes every 4 beats, each slightly faster. The piano shifts from quarter-notes to eighths to sixteenths as the tempo rises.

[VISUAL: A score with tempo markings rising: ♩=80, ♩=100, ♩=120, ♩=140, ♩=160, ♩=180, ♩=200. Below, the piano part shifts from quarters to eighths to sixteenths, the note-sprites animating faster and faster.]


---

## Notes and Additional Considerations from r2 draft

*The following material comes from an earlier or parallel revision draft (r2 draft). It is preserved here because content costs thought — nothing gets thrown away. Some passages restate the chapter's core ideas in a different voice; others introduce examples or angles not covered above. Read as supplemental exercises for the same discipline.*

### The Opening: Bell-Tolling Chords (Moderato, mm. 1–4)

The concerto begins with solo piano: eight solemn chords in C minor, marked *Moderato* and *forte*, each separated by silence. The chords are thick (8–10 notes each), spanning four octaves, and they ring like cathedral bells. There is no tempo yet — the chords are *a tempo libero*, each slightly longer than the last, building suspense.

The harmonic progression is:
1. **C minor tonic** (C–Eb–G, octave-doubled, bass C1 and C2).
2. **Dominant seventh** (G7, with F in the bass).
3. **Return to tonic**, wider voicing.
4. **Augmented sixth** (German sixth → dominant).
5. **Dominant**, held.
6. **Tonic**, fff, full keyboard.

Each chord is a `note/strike` event, but **spread** — the notes do not all start at the same instant; they bloom slightly (a *rolled chord*, but so tight it reads as simultaneous). We will model this by staggering the attack by 10–30 milliseconds per note, bottom to top.

```scheme
;; Rachmaninoff Piano Concerto No. 2, Op. 18
;; Movement I (Moderato), mm. 1–4: opening chords (solo piano)
;; Bell-tolling C minor chords, free tempo, each slightly longer

(define (rolled-chord pitches base-time spread-ms velocity)
  ;; Strike each pitch in sequence, staggered by spread-ms
  (let loop ((ps pitches) (offset 0))
    (when (pair? ps)
      (note/strike (car ps) 
                   (+ base-time (/ offset 1000.0)) 
                   2.0 
                   velocity)
      (loop (cdr ps) (+ offset spread-ms)))))

(define (opening-chords)
  ;; Chord 1: C minor tonic, wide voicing (C1 Eb1 G1 C2 Eb2 G2 C3 Eb3)
  (rolled-chord '(36 39 43 48 51 55 60 63) 0.0 20 0.85)
  
  ;; Chord 2: G7/F (F1 G1 B1 D2 F2 G2 B2 D3), slightly louder
  (rolled-chord '(41 43 47 50 53 55 59 62) 3.0 22 0.88)
  
  ;; Chord 3: C minor, wider (C1 G1 C2 Eb2 G2 C3 Eb3 G3 C4)
  (rolled-chord '(36 43 48 51 55 60 63 67 72) 6.5 25 0.90)
  
  ;; Chord 4: German sixth resolving (Ab1 C2 Eb2 F#2 Ab2 C3 Eb3 F#3)
  (rolled-chord '(44 48 51 54 56 60 63 66) 10.5 28 0.92)
  
  ;; Chord 5: G dominant (G1 D2 F2 G2 B2 D3 F3 G3 B3)
  (rolled-chord '(43 50 53 55 59 62 65 67 71) 15.0 30 0.94)
  
  ;; Chord 6: C minor tonic, full octave spread, fff
  (rolled-chord '(24 36 39 43 48 51 55 60 63 67 72) 20.0 35 1.0))

(opening-chords)
```

<!-- BUILD: wire rolled-chord to the scheduler; each note scheduled at base-time + offset; sustain=2.0 so chords ring and overlap slightly; verify the stagger is audible but tight (20–35ms spread feels \"simultaneous but blooming\") -->

[VISUAL: A grand staff (treble + bass clefs, joined by brace). The first chord is notated: bass clef shows C1–Eb1–G1–C2, treble clef shows Eb2–G2–C3–Eb3, each note a whole-note sprite (48×48) in black ink on the dot-matrix substrate. A fermata sits above the top note. The chord sprites glow faintly and bob slowly (whole-note tempo). Beside the staff, a time ruler shows the 20ms stagger visually as a tiny cascade.]

**Technique:** The *rolled chord* is a Romantic piano idiom. By staggering the attack, you make a dense voicing sound *fuller* — the ear hears each pitch bloom into the chord, rather than a percussive thud. Rachmaninoff uses this constantly; we model it with a `spread-ms` parameter. In a real performance, the spread might be 15–50ms depending on tempo and touch.

