### The First Theme: Clarinet Melody with Pizzicato (Moderato, mm. 50–58)

After the opening chords and a long orchestral buildup, the *first theme* enters at measure 50: a lyrical, yearning melody in E-flat major, first stated by **solo clarinet** (doubled by oboe), accompanied by **pizzicato strings** (short, plucked notes).

The melody is eight bars, 4/4, marked *espressivo*. We will render:
- **Clarinet voice** (a warm, reedy section-voice — Chapter 7 technique).
- **Pizzicato strings** (short decay, no sustain — Chapter 8 envelope trick).
- **Tempo rubato** (slight ritardando in bar 4, then *a tempo* — Chapter 13).

Melodic line (E-flat major, starting on G4):
```
G4 (quarter) – Bb4 (quarter) – C5 (half)
Bb4 (quarter) – Ab4 (quarter) – G4 (quarter) – F4 (quarter)
Eb4 (half) – F4 (quarter) – G4 (quarter)
Ab4 (dotted-half) – [rit.] – G4 (quarter, held)
```

Pizzicato accompaniment: Eb2–Bb2–G3 (eighth-note ostinato, one chord per beat).

```scheme
;; Rachmaninoff Concerto No. 2, Movement I, mm. 50–58
;; First theme: clarinet melody (Eb major) with pizzicato strings

(define (section-voice-clarinet)
  ;; Warm, reedy harmonic profile (fundamental + strong 3rd/5th harmonics)
  ;; [needs: GAP-6 — createPeriodicWave section-voice tuning]
  ;; For now, simulate with a single note + implied timbre
  'clarinet-voice)

(define (pizzicato-envelope pitch time velocity)
  ;; Short attack, instant decay, no sustain (plucked string)
  ;; [needs: GAP-3 — ADSR envelope control]
  ;; Simulate with very short duration
  (note/strike pitch time 0.15 velocity))

(define (first-theme)
  (let ((tempo 72)  ; bpm, Moderato
        (beat (/ 60.0 72)))
    ;; Clarinet melody (voice implied)
    (note/strike 67 (* 0 beat) (* 1 beat) 0.70)  ; G4 quarter
    (note/strike 70 (* 1 beat) (* 1 beat) 0.72)  ; Bb4 quarter
    (note/strike 72 (* 2 beat) (* 2 beat) 0.75)  ; C5 half
    (note/strike 70 (* 4 beat) (* 1 beat) 0.73)  ; Bb4 quarter
    (note/strike 68 (* 5 beat) (* 1 beat) 0.71)  ; Ab4 quarter
    (note/strike 67 (* 6 beat) (* 1 beat) 0.70)  ; G4 quarter
    (note/strike 65 (* 7 beat) (* 1 beat) 0.68)  ; F4 quarter
    (note/strike 63 (* 8 beat) (* 2 beat) 0.75)  ; Eb4 half
    (note/strike 65 (* 10 beat) (* 1 beat) 0.70) ; F4 quarter
    (note/strike 67 (* 11 beat) (* 1 beat) 0.72) ; G4 quarter
    ;; Ritardando in bar 4 (stretch the last two beats by 1.2x)
    (note/strike 68 (* 12 beat) (* 3 beat 1.2) 0.80) ; Ab4 dotted-half, rit
    (note/strike 67 (* 15 beat 1.2) (* 1 beat 1.3) 0.78) ; G4 quarter, held
    
    ;; Pizzicato strings (Eb2–Bb2–G3 triad, eighth-note pulse, 16 beats)
    (let loop ((b 0))
      (when (< b 16)
        (pizzicato-envelope 39 (* b beat 0.5) 0.55)  ; Eb2
        (pizzicato-envelope 46 (* b beat 0.5) 0.50)  ; Bb2
        (pizzicato-envelope 55 (* b beat 0.5) 0.48)  ; G3
        (loop (+ b 1))))))

(first-theme)
```

<!-- BUILD: wire section-voice-clarinet to a warm harmonic profile (rich 2nd/3rd harmonics, soft attack) once GAP-6 is closed; pizzicato-envelope should trigger very short sustain (0.1–0.2s) to simulate plucked string; ritardando is modeled by stretching beat duration in bars 12–15 by 1.2–1.3x; verify the melody sounds lyrical and the pizz is crisp, detached -->

[VISUAL: A single staff in treble clef, key signature Eb major (3 flats). The melody is notated as quarter and half notes, with a ritardando marking (\"rit.\") above bars 4. Below the staff, a second staff (bass clef) shows the pizzicato chords as staccato eighth-notes, each chord marked with a dot above (staccato). The note-sprites for the melody (quarter/half, 48×48) bob at a moderate tempo; the pizz sprites (eighth, 16×16) are jittery and quick.]

**Technique:** The clarinet voice is **section-voiced** — one clarinet in the score, but we render it as a tuned harmonic profile that sounds like a whole woodwind section (Chapter 7). The pizzicato is an **envelope trick**: instant attack, zero sustain, short decay. This is the orchestral equivalent of a bass-line `beat` pattern, but pitched and harmonic.

