### Cadenza Flourish: Scalar Runs in Octaves (Moderato, Coda)

Near the end of the first movement, the piano has a brief **cadenza** — a solo passage, unaccompanied, *ad libitum*. The cadenza is built from rapid **scalar runs** (ascending and descending C minor scale, three octaves) with **octave doubling** (the right hand plays the scale, the left hand doubles it two octaves lower).

The run is marked *prestissimo* (as fast as possible), with a crescendo from *p* to *ff* over the ascent, then a decrescendo back to *p* on the descent.

We will generate the scale programmatically (C minor = C D Eb F G Ab Bb C), then schedule each note with a very short duration (sixteenth-note at tempo 180 bpm → ~0.08 seconds per note).

```scheme
;; Rachmaninoff Concerto No. 2, Movement I (Coda)
;; Cadenza flourish: C minor scale runs, octave-doubled, prestissimo

(define (c-minor-scale start-pitch octaves)
  ;; Generate C minor scale (natural minor) for `octaves` octaves
  ;; C=0, D=2, Eb=3, F=5, G=7, Ab=8, Bb=10, C=12 (semitone offsets)
  (let ((pattern '(0 2 3 5 7 8 10 12)))
    (let loop ((oct 0) (result '()))
      (if (>= oct octaves)
          (reverse result)
          (loop (+ oct 1)
                (append (reverse (map (lambda (offset)
                                        (+ start-pitch (* oct 12) offset))
                                      pattern))
                        result))))))

(define (scalar-run pitches start-time note-duration crescendo-start crescendo-end)
  ;; Play each pitch in sequence, with velocity ramping from crescendo-start to crescendo-end
  (let* ((count (length pitches))
         (velocity-step (/ (- crescendo-end crescendo-start) count)))
    (let loop ((ps pitches) (i 0))
      (when (pair? ps)
        (let ((vel (+ crescendo-start (* i velocity-step))))
          ;; Octave doubling: play the note, and the note two octaves lower
          (note/strike (car ps) 
                       (+ start-time (* i note-duration)) 
                       note-duration 
                       vel)
          (note/strike (- (car ps) 24)  ; two octaves lower
                       (+ start-time (* i note-duration)) 
                       note-duration 
                       vel)
          (loop (cdr ps) (+ i 1)))))))

(define (cadenza-runs)
  (let* ((tempo 180)  ; prestissimo
         (beat (/ 60.0 tempo))
         (sixteenth (* beat 0.25))
         (scale-up (c-minor-scale 60 3))    ; C4 to C7 (3 octaves ascending)
         (scale-down (reverse scale-up)))    ; C7 to C4 (descending)
    ;; Ascending run: p to ff (0.4 → 1.0)
    (scalar-run scale-up 0.0 sixteenth 0.4 1.0)
    ;; Descending run: ff to p (1.0 → 0.4)
    (scalar-run scale-down 
                (+ (* (length scale-up) sixteenth) 0.2)  ; slight pause at top
                sixteenth 
                1.0 
                0.4)))

(cadenza-runs)
```

<!-- BUILD: wire scalar-run to the scheduler; each note scheduled at start-time + (i * note-duration); octave doubling is literal (same pitch - 24 semitones, same time); verify the crescendo ramp is audible (velocity stepping from 0.4 to 1.0 over ~24 notes); the descending run should start 0.2s after the ascending run ends (brief pause at the apex) -->

[VISUAL: Two staves (treble + bass clefs, brace-joined). The ascending run is notated as a long beam of thirty-second-note sprites (16×16, very dense, cascading upward from C4 to C7). A crescendo hairpin is drawn beneath, from *p* to *ff*. The descending run mirrors it, with a decrescendo hairpin. The note-sprites are in rapid motion, jittering at thirty-second tempo. A tempo marking \"Prestissimo\" appears above.]

**Technique:** This is **generative scalar writing**. Instead of hand-coding 48 notes, we generate the scale programmatically (`c-minor-scale`), then map over it to schedule each note. The octave doubling is a simple pitch offset (`- 24` semitones). The crescendo is modeled as a linear velocity ramp. This is a Chapter 15 structure technique — using list manipulation to build large musical gestures.

---


### The Adagio Theme: Flute Solo with Piano Ornaments (Movement II, mm. 18–26)

The second movement (*Adagio sostenuto*) is in E major, 4/4, marked *molto espressivo*. The main theme is one of the most famous melodies in the repertoire: a long, singing line first stated by **solo flute**, then echoed by the **piano** with added ornaments (grace notes, trills).

We will render the first 8 bars:
- **Flute solo** (mm. 18–21): the melody, pure and unadorned.
- **Piano echo** (mm. 22–25): the same melody, but with grace notes and a trill on the final note.

Melody (E major, starting on G#4):
```
G#4 (dotted-quarter) – F#4 (eighth) – E4 (quarter) – D#4 (quarter)
E4 (half) – C#4 (quarter) – D#4 (quarter)
E4 (dotted-half) – [trill on E4] – F#4 (quarter)
G#4 (whole, tied into next bar)
```

Grace notes (piano version, mm. 22): a quick D#4→E4 grace before the first E4.

```scheme
;; Rachmaninoff Concerto No. 2, Movement II (Adagio sostenuto), mm. 18–26
;; Flute solo, then piano echo with ornaments (E major theme)

(define (grace-note main-pitch grace-pitch start-time main-duration velocity)
  ;; A grace note is very short (1/32 of the main duration), stolen from the main note's attack
  (let ((grace-dur (* main-duration 0.03)))
    (note/strike grace-pitch start-time grace-dur (* velocity 0.8))
    (note/strike main-pitch (+ start-time grace-dur) (- main-duration grace-dur) velocity)))

(define (trill pitch start-time duration velocity interval)
  ;; A trill alternates between pitch and pitch+interval (usually 1 or 2 semitones)
  ;; Trill speed: 16 alternations per beat (very fast, Romantic style)
  ;; [needs: GAP-2 — trill notation glyph]
  (let* ((alternations 16)
         (step (/ duration alternations)))
    (let loop ((i 0))
      (when (< i alternations)
        (note/strike (if (even? i) pitch (+ pitch interval))
                     (+ start-time (* i step))
                     step
                     velocity)
        (loop (+ i 1))))))

(define (adagio-theme)
  (let ((tempo 52)  ; Adagio sostenuto (very slow)
        (beat (/ 60.0 52)))
    ;; Flute solo (mm. 18–21), pure melody
    (note/strike 68 (* 0 beat) (* 1.5 beat) 0.65)  ; G#4 dotted-quarter
    (note/strike 66 (* 1.5 beat) (* 0.5 beat) 0.63) ; F#4 eighth
    (note/strike 64 (* 2 beat) (* 1 beat) 0.65)    ; E4 quarter
    (note/strike 63 (* 3 beat) (* 1 beat) 0.62)    ; D#4 quarter
    (note/strike 64 (* 4 beat) (* 2 beat) 0.70)    ; E4 half
    (note/strike 61 (* 6 beat) (* 1 beat) 0.60)    ; C#4 quarter
    (note/strike 63 (* 7 beat) (* 1 beat) 0.62)    ; D#4 quarter
    ;; Trill on E4 (bar 5, last beat)
    (trill 64 (* 8 beat) (* 3 beat) 0.68 2)        ; E4 dotted-half, trill (interval=2 semitones, F#4)
    (note/strike 66 (* 11 beat) (* 1 beat) 0.65)   ; F#4 quarter
    (note/strike 68 (* 12 beat) (* 4 beat) 0.70)   ; G#4 whole (tied)
    
    ;; Piano echo (mm. 22–25), same melody with grace notes
    (let ((offset (* 16 beat)))
      ;; Grace note before first E4 (D#4 → E4)
      (grace-note 64 63 (+ offset (* 2 beat)) (* 1 beat) 0.72)
      (note/strike 63 (+ offset (* 3 beat)) (* 1 beat) 0.70)  ; D#4
      (note/strike 64 (+ offset (* 4 beat)) (* 2 beat) 0.75)  ; E4 half
      (note/strike 61 (+ offset (* 6 beat)) (* 1 beat) 0.68)  ; C#4
      (note/strike 63 (+ offset (* 7 beat)) (* 1 beat) 0.70)  ; D#4
      ;; Trill on E4, piano version (slightly longer, more ornate)
      (trill 64 (+ offset (* 8 beat)) (* 3 beat) 0.78 2)
      (note/strike 66 (+ offset (* 11 beat)) (* 1 beat) 0.75)
      (note/strike 68 (+ offset (* 12 beat)) (* 4 beat) 0.80))))

(adagio-theme)
```

<!-- BUILD: wire grace-note and trill to the scheduler; grace-note steals 3% of the main note's duration (typical Romantic proportion); trill alternates pitch ±interval at 16 steps per duration (very fast, audible as a \"shimmer\"); verify the flute (first 16 beats) sounds pure, the piano (second 16 beats) sounds ornamented; the trill should be clearly audible as rapid alternation, not a blur -->

[VISUAL: Two systems. Top system (mm. 18–21): treble clef, key signature E major (4 sharps), the flute melody notated with dotted-quarter, eighth, quarter, half, whole-note sprites. A trill mark (wavy line, *[needs: GAP-2]*) sits above the E4 in bar 5. Bottom system (mm. 22–25): the same melody, but with a grace-note slash before the first E4, and a longer trill mark. The flute sprites glow pale blue; the piano sprites glow warm amber.]

**Technique:** The **grace note** is an ornament that \"steals\" time from the main note. We model it by playing a very short note (3% of the main note's duration) immediately before the main attack. The **trill** is rapid alternation between two pitches (usually a whole-tone or semitone apart). Rachmaninoff uses trills for expressive *intensity* — the trill on E4 is marked *con passione* in the score. By rendering the same melody twice (flute pure, piano ornamented), we show how orchestration and ornamentation are two sides of the same coin.

---


### The Finale Opening: Triplet Drive (Allegro scherzando, mm. 1–8)

The third movement (*Allegro scherzando*) is in C minor, 2/2 (cut time), marked *vivace* (lively, fast). It opens with a driving **triplet figure** in the piano's right hand (eighth-note triplets, molto leggiero — very light) against a syncopated **staccato bass** in the left hand and pizzicato strings.

The triplet pattern (C minor arpeggio, ascending):
```
C4–Eb4–G4 (triplet), repeated, then C4–Eb4–Ab4, then C4–F4–Ab4, resolving to G4–D4–G3 (dominant).
```

The bass line (left hand + pizzicato cellos):
```
C2 (half-note, beat 1) – [rest] – G2 (quarter, syncopated on beat 2.5) – C2 (quarter, beat 3).
```

We will render 8 bars of this, with the triplet figure in the piano and the bass line doubled by strings.

```scheme
;; Rachmaninoff Concerto No. 2, Movement III (Allegro scherzando), mm. 1–8
;; Triplet drive: piano triplets (C minor arpeggio) with syncopated bass

(define (triplet-figure pitches start-time beat-duration velocity)
  ;; Play three pitches evenly spaced within one beat (eighth-note triplets in 2/2)
  ;; [needs: GAP-1 — triplet duration encoding in NOTE_VALUE_BEATS]
  (let ((triplet-dur (/ beat-duration 3.0)))
    (note/strike (list-ref pitches 0) start-time triplet-dur velocity)
    (note/strike (list-ref pitches 1) (+ start-time triplet-dur) triplet-dur velocity)
    (note/strike (list-ref pitches 2) (+ start-time (* 2 triplet-dur)) triplet-dur velocity)))

(define (finale-opening)
  (let* ((tempo 138)  ; Allegro scherzando (cut time, so feels like 138 half-notes/min)
         (beat (/ 60.0 138))  ; one half-note beat
         (bar (* 2 beat)))    ; 2/2 time signature
    ;; Piano triplets (right hand, mm. 1–8)
    ;; Bar 1: C4–Eb4–G4 (repeated 4 times, two beats each)
    (triplet-figure '(60 63 67) (* 0 beat) beat 0.60)
    (triplet-figure '(60 63 67) (* 1 beat) beat 0.60)
    ;; Bar 2: C4–Eb4–Ab4 (twice)
    (triplet-figure '(60 63 68) (* 2 beat) beat 0.62)
    (triplet-figure '(60 63 68) (* 3 beat) beat 0.62)
    ;; Bar 3: C4–F4–Ab4 (twice)
    (triplet-figure '(60 65 68) (* 4 beat) beat 0.63)
    (triplet-figure '(60 65 68) (* 5 beat) beat 0.63)
    ;; Bar 4: G4–D4–G3 (dominant resolution)
    (triplet-figure '(67 62 55) (* 6 beat) beat 0.65)
    (triplet-figure '(67 62 55) (* 7 beat) beat 0.65)
    ;; Repeat pattern for bars 5–8 (same as 1–4, but louder)
    (triplet-figure '(60 63 67) (* 8 beat) beat 0.68)
    (triplet-figure '(60 63 67) (* 9 beat) beat 0.68)
    (triplet-figure '(60 63 68) (* 10 beat) beat 0.70)
    (triplet-figure '(60 63 68) (* 11 beat) beat 0.70)
    (triplet-figure '(60 65 68) (* 12 beat) beat 0.72)
    (triplet-figure '(60 65 68) (* 13 beat) beat 0.72)
    (triplet-figure '(67 62 55) (* 14 beat) beat 0.75)
    (triplet-figure '(67 62 55) (* 15 beat) beat 0.75)
    
    ;; Bass line (left hand + pizzicato strings, mm. 1–8)
    ;; Syncopated pattern: C2 (beat 1) – [rest] – G2 (beat 1.5) – C2 (beat 2)
    (let loop ((b 0))
      (when (< b 8)
        (note/strike 36 (* b bar) (* 1 beat) 0.70)              ; C2, half-note
        (note/strike 43 (+ (* b bar) (* 1.5 beat)) (* 0.5 beat) 0.65)  ; G2, syncopated quarter
        (note/strike 36 (+ (* b bar) (* 1.75 beat)) (* 0.25 beat) 0.68) ; C2, short
        (loop (+ b 1))))))

(finale-opening)
```

<!-- BUILD: wire triplet-figure to the scheduler; each triplet note is exactly 1/3 of the beat duration (currently simulated; will use GAP-1 triplet encoding once available); verify the triplet figure sounds rapid and light (leggiero); the bass line should sound syncopated (the G2 on beat 1.5 disrupts the downbeat expectation); verify the pattern repeats with rising velocity (crescendo over 8 bars) -->

[VISUAL: Two staves (treble + bass, brace-joined). Top staff: key signature C minor (3 flats), time signature 2/2. The triplet figure is notated as beamed eighth-notes with a \"3\" bracket above each group. The triplet sprites (eighth-note, 16×16) are jittery and fast. Bottom staff: the bass line, half-notes and syncopated quarters, each marked staccato (dot above). A metronome marking \"♩ = 138\" appears above. The triplet sprites are in rapid motion; the bass sprites bob at half-note tempo but with syncopated accents.]

**Technique:** The **triplet** is a rhythmic division (3 notes in the time of 2). In 2/2 time, a half-note beat normally divides into two quarters or four eighths; a triplet divides it into *three* eighths. This creates a rolling, perpetual-motion feel. The syncopated bass (accents on off-beats) gives the pattern drive. This is a Chapter 10 polyrhythmic idea (triplet against duple) applied at high speed.

---


### Climactic Tutti: Full Orchestra + Piano (Allegro scherzando, Recapitulation)

Near the end of the third movement, the main theme returns in the **recapitulation**, now *fortissimo* and in the **full orchestra** (all sections) **plus** the piano in octaves. This is the loudest, densest moment in the entire concerto — a wall of sound.

We will render 4 bars of the recapitulation:
- **Strings** (section-voiced, violins + violas + cellos + basses, all in octaves).
- **Woodwinds** (flutes + oboes + clarinets, tripled).
- **Brass** (horns + trumpets + trombones, quadrupled).
- **Piano** (right hand in octaves, left hand in thick chords).
- **Tutti dynamic** = fff (velocity 1.0 across the board).

The harmonic progression is a simple **C minor tonic → dominant → tonic** cadence, but rendered with every available voice.

```scheme
;; Rachmaninoff Concerto No. 2, Movement III (Recapitulation)
;; Climactic tutti: full orchestra + piano, fff, C minor cadence

(define (tutti-chord pitches start-time duration velocity)
  ;; All voices play the same pitches simultaneously (tutti = \"all\")
  ;; Strings, woodwinds, brass, piano — each section doubled/tripled
  ;; [needs: GAP-6 — section-voice tuning for strings/woodwinds/brass]
  (for-each (lambda (p)
              ;; Simulate multiple sections by slight detune spread
              (note/strike p start-time duration velocity)
              (note/strike p start-time duration velocity)  ; doubled
              (note/strike (+ p 0.05) start-time duration velocity)) ; detuned +5 cents
            pitches))

(define (climactic-tutti)
  (let* ((tempo 144)  ; Allegro, faster now (final push)
         (beat (/ 60.0 144))
         (bar (* 2 beat)))
    ;; Bar 1: C minor tonic (C2 C3 Eb3 G3 C4 Eb4 G4 C5), fff
    (tutti-chord '(36 48 51 55 60 63 67 72) 0.0 bar 1.0)
    ;; Bar 2: G dominant (G2 G3 B3 D4 F4 G4 B4 D5), fff
    (tutti-chord '(43 55 59 62 65 67 71 74) bar bar 1.0)
    ;; Bar 3: C minor tonic, even wider (C1 C2 Eb2 G2 C3 Eb3 G3 C4 Eb4 G4 C5), fff
    (tutti-chord '(24 36 39 43 48 51 55 60 63 67 72) (* 2 bar) bar 1.0)
    ;; Bar 4: Final tonic, all octaves, held (whole-note)
    (tutti-chord '(24 36 48 60 72) (* 3 bar) (* 2 bar) 1.0)))

(climactic-tutti)
```

