[VISUAL: A grand staff with an additional staff above (for winds) and below (for bass). All three staves show the same chord (C minor tonic, wide voicing) notated as whole-notes, each marked \"fff\" (triple-forte). The note-sprites (whole-note, 48×48) are large, glowing intensely, and bob slowly in unison. A fermata sits above the top note. The palette is saturated — deep reds and golds for the forte marking, bright white for the note-heads.]

**Technique:** A **tutti** (Italian: \"all\") is when the entire ensemble plays together. This is the opposite of the solo passages (clarinet, flute, piano cadenza) earlier in the chapter. In a real orchestral tutti, you might have 60+ players on the same chord. We simulate this by **doubling** each pitch (playing it multiple times) and adding a **slight detune** (+5 cents, or 5% of a semitone) to one voice. This creates a **chorus effect** — the ear hears one massive chord, but with natural beating and richness. This is a Chapter 14 orchestration technique, pushed to the maximum.

