### Structural Interlude: Organizing a Multi-Movement Work

The six examples above are **fragments** from three movements. In a real performance, the concerto is a single continuous experience (though the movements are separated by brief pauses). How do you structure this in code?

One approach is to define each movement as a **separate function**, then call them in sequence with measured silence between:

```scheme
;; Rachmaninoff Concerto No. 2, Op. 18 — full structure (movements I, II, III)

(define (movement-i)
  ;; Opening chords, first theme, cadenza (from earlier examples)
  (opening-chords)
  ;; [... rest of movement I ...]
  )

(define (movement-ii)
  ;; Adagio theme, flute + piano (from earlier examples)
  (adagio-theme)
  ;; [... rest of movement II ...]
  )

(define (movement-iii)
  ;; Finale opening triplets, climactic tutti (from earlier examples)
  (finale-opening)
  (climactic-tutti)
  ;; [... rest of movement III ...]
  )

(define (concerto-full)
  (movement-i)
  ;; Pause between movements: 3 seconds of silence
  (note/strike 0 (* 16 60.0 72) 3.0 0.0)  ; dummy silent note for spacing
  (movement-ii)
  (note/strike 0 (* 32 60.0 52) 3.0 0.0)
  (movement-iii))

(concerto-full)
```

<!-- BUILD: wire concerto-full to the scheduler; each movement is a function that schedules its own notes; the \"pause\" is simulated by a silent note (pitch 0, velocity 0, duration 3.0s) placed at the end of each movement's timeline; verify the movements play in sequence with audible gaps -->

**Technique:** This is a **Chapter 15 structure technique** — using functions to organize large-scale form. Each movement is self-contained, but they are **composed** (in the functional-programming sense) into a single performance. The silent \"spacer\" notes are a hack (the engine doesn't yet have a `(rest duration)` primitive), but they work. This is how you would structure a symphony, a suite, or any multi-movement work.

