### Encoding the Full Concerto: A Scaffolding Strategy

Transcribing the *entire* Rachmaninoff Second (30+ minutes, three movements, ~3000 bars) is beyond the scope of this chapter — but the **strategy** is important, because it generalizes to any large work.

**Step 1: Identify the structural sections.**
- Movement I: Exposition (themes A + B), Development, Recapitulation, Coda.
- Movement II: ABA form (theme, contrasting middle, theme returns).
- Movement III: Rondo (ABACABA).

Each section is a **function**.

**Step 2: Encode the themes.**
- Each theme is a melody + harmony + rhythm. Encode it as a list of pitches + durations + velocities. Example:

```scheme
(define theme-a-melody
  '((60 1.0 0.70)   ; C4, quarter-note, mf
    (63 1.0 0.72)   ; Eb4
    (67 2.0 0.75))) ; G4, half-note

(define (play-melody theme start-time)
  (let loop ((notes theme) (t start-time))
    (when (pair? notes)
      (let ((pitch (caar notes))
            (dur (cadar notes))
            (vel (caddar notes)))
        (note/strike pitch t dur vel)
        (loop (cdr notes) (+ t dur))))))
```

**Step 3: Encode the accompaniment.**
- Chords, basslines, ostinatos — each is a separate function. Combine them with the melody using `let` or by calling them in parallel (same start-time).

**Step 4: Orchestrate.**
- Assign each theme to a section-voice (strings, woodwinds, brass, piano). Use the `tutti-chord` technique for full-orchestra moments, and solo voices for exposed passages.

**Step 5: Assemble the movements.**
- Each movement is a sequence of function calls (themes + transitions + codas). Add rests/pauses between movements.

**Step 6: Test incrementally.**
- Render one theme at a time. Verify it sounds correct. Then add the next theme. Build the movement from the ground up.

This is how you would encode *any* large-scale work — a symphony, an opera, a Mass. The Rach 2 is just one (very famous) example.

---


### A Note on Public Domain and Musical Fidelity

Rachmaninoff's Piano Concerto No. 2 is **public domain** in most jurisdictions (composed 1900–1901; Rachmaninoff died 1943, exceeding the 70-year post-mortem threshold in the EU and most other countries; it is PD in the US as well, as a pre-1928 publication).

However, **specific recordings** are still under copyright (the performance, not the composition). When we say \"render Rachmaninoff,\" we mean:
- **Encode the score** (the notes, rhythms, dynamics, articulations as written by Rachmaninoff).
- **DO NOT transcribe a specific recording** (e.g., do not copy the exact tempo, phrasing, or ornamentation choices of a particular pianist or conductor — those are the performer's creative choices and may be copyrighted as a derivative work).

Our goal is **musical fidelity to the score**, not fidelity to a recording. If you have access to the public-domain score (available from IMSLP, the International Music Score Library Project), use that as your source. If you are working from a modern edition, verify it is a scholarly edition based on the original manuscript, not a copyrighted arrangement.

This is the same principle we use for Twinkle Twinkle, world-percussion patterns, and all other musical material in the book: **public domain or original only**.

---


### A Chamber Reduction: Concerto for Piano and String Quartet

One way to explore the Rach 2 without needing a full orchestra is to render a **chamber reduction** — the same music, but arranged for a smaller ensemble. This is a common practice for studying large works: Beethoven's symphonies have piano-duet reductions, Brahms's Requiem has a piano-vocal reduction, etc.

We will take the **Adagio theme** (Movement II) and arrange it for **piano + string quartet** (two violins, viola, cello). This reduces the orchestral texture to 5 voices, making it easier to hear each line.

```scheme
;; Rachmaninoff Concerto No. 2, Movement II (Adagio sostenuto)
;; Chamber reduction: piano + string quartet (2 violins, viola, cello)

(define (string-voice pitch start-time duration velocity instrument)
  ;; Simulate a string section-voice (violin, viola, cello)
  ;; [needs: GAP-6 — createPeriodicWave for string timbres]
  ;; Each instrument has a distinct harmonic profile
  (note/strike pitch start-time duration velocity))

(define (chamber-adagio)
  (let ((tempo 52)
        (beat (/ 60.0 52)))
    ;; Piano: the main melody (as in the earlier example, mm. 18–21)
    (note/strike 68 (* 0 beat) (* 1.5 beat) 0.65)  ; G#4 dotted-quarter
    (note/strike 66 (* 1.5 beat) (* 0.5 beat) 0.63) ; F#4 eighth
    (note/strike 64 (* 2 beat) (* 1 beat) 0.65)    ; E4 quarter
    (note/strike 63 (* 3 beat) (* 1 beat) 0.62)    ; D#4 quarter
    (note/strike 64 (* 4 beat) (* 2 beat) 0.70)    ; E4 half
    (note/strike 61 (* 6 beat) (* 1 beat) 0.60)    ; C#4 quarter
    (note/strike 63 (* 7 beat) (* 1 beat) 0.62)    ; D#4 quarter
    (trill 64 (* 8 beat) (* 3 beat) 0.68 2)        ; E4 trill
    (note/strike 66 (* 11 beat) (* 1 beat) 0.65)   ; F#4 quarter
    (note/strike 68 (* 12 beat) (* 4 beat) 0.70)   ; G#4 whole
    
    ;; Strings: sustained harmony (E major triad, distributed across 4 voices)
    ;; Violin I: B4 (sustained, pp)
    (string-voice 71 0.0 (* 16 beat) 0.40 'violin)
    ;; Violin II: G#4 (sustained, pp)
    (string-voice 68 0.0 (* 16 beat) 0.38 'violin)
    ;; Viola: E4 (sustained, pp)
    (string-voice 64 0.0 (* 16 beat) 0.36 'viola)
    ;; Cello: E3 (sustained, pp, then moves to C#3 at bar 3)
    (string-voice 52 0.0 (* 6 beat) 0.40 'cello)
    (string-voice 49 (* 6 beat) (* 10 beat) 0.38 'cello)))

(chamber-adagio)
```

<!-- BUILD: wire chamber-adagio to the scheduler; the piano melody is identical to the earlier solo-flute version (reuse the same note sequence); the string voices are sustained whole-notes and half-notes, very soft (pp = velocity 0.36–0.40), creating a \"pad\" beneath the melody; verify the melody stands out (piano is louder, 0.60–0.70) and the strings are a soft halo around it -->

[VISUAL: A chamber-music score (5 staves: violin I, violin II, viola, cello, piano). The top four staves show whole-notes and half-notes (the sustained harmony), each marked \"pp\". The bottom staff (piano, grand staff) shows the melody as in the earlier example. The note-sprites on the string staves are large (whole-note, 48×48) and glow very faintly; the piano sprites are brighter. A tempo marking \"Adagio sostenuto ♩ = 52\" appears above.]

**Technique:** A **chamber reduction** is not just \"play the same notes with fewer players.\" It requires **re-voicing** — deciding which notes are essential, which can be omitted, and how to distribute them across the available instruments. Here, we:
- Keep the **melody** in the piano (unchanged).
- Reduce the **orchestral accompaniment** to a simple triad (E–G#–B), sustained across the four string voices.
- Omit the inner voices and countermelodies (they would clutter the texture in a small ensemble).

This is a **Chapter 14 orchestration** technique, applied in reverse: instead of expanding a piano part to orchestra, we *contract* an orchestral part to chamber ensemble.

