### Polyphonic Texture: Three Independent Lines in the Coda

The final example is a **polyphonic texture** from the Moderato coda: three independent melodic lines (piano right hand, piano left hand, cello) that move simultaneously but do not align rhythmically. This is **Chapter 9 polyphony**, but at a higher difficulty level (faster tempo, wider intervals, more ornate).

```scheme
;; Rachmaninoff Concerto No. 2, Movement I (Coda)
;; Polyphonic texture: three independent lines (piano RH, piano LH, cello)

(define (polyphonic-coda)
  (let ((tempo 96)
        (beat (/ 60.0 96)))
    ;; Piano right hand: descending chromatic line (C5 → C4, 13 notes, eighth-notes)
    (let loop ((pitch 72) (t 0.0))
      (when (>= pitch 60)
        (note/strike pitch t (* 0.5 beat) 0.75)
        (loop (- pitch 1) (+ t (* 0.5 beat)))))
    
    ;; Piano left hand: arpeggiated C minor triad (C2 Eb2 G2 C3, quarter-notes, offset by 1 beat)
    (note/strike 36 (* 1 beat) beat 0.70)   ; C2
    (note/strike 39 (* 2 beat) beat 0.70)   ; Eb2
    (note/strike 43 (* 3 beat) beat 0.70)   ; G2
    (note/strike 48 (* 4 beat) beat 0.70)   ; C3
    (note/strike 36 (* 5 beat) beat 0.70)   ; C2 (repeat)
    
    ;; Cello: sustained G2 (whole-note, pp, underneath both piano lines)
    (note/strike 43 0.0 (* 8 beat) 0.50)))

(polyphonic-coda)
```

<!-- BUILD: wire polyphonic-coda to the scheduler; verify the three lines are audible as distinct (RH descending chromatic is fast and high, LH arpeggio is slower and mid-range, cello is sustained and low); the lines do NOT align — the RH starts at beat 0, the LH starts at beat 1, the cello sustains from beat 0 through beat 8 -->

[VISUAL: Three staves (piano grand staff + cello staff below). Top staff: descending chromatic line (C5 to C4, beamed eighth-notes). Middle staff: arpeggiated triad (C2–Eb2–G2–C3, quarter-notes). Bottom staff: whole-note G2, marked \"pp\". The note-sprites on each staff are in independent motion: eighth-note sprites (top) are jittery, quarter-note sprites (middle) are steady, whole-note sprite (bottom) is slow and languid. A label \"3 independent voices\" appears beside the staves.]

**Technique:** This is **three-voice counterpoint** (Chapter 9) applied to a late-Romantic texture. The lines are independent in **pitch** (chromatic descent vs. arpeggio vs. sustained tone), **rhythm** (eighth-notes vs. quarter-notes vs. whole-note), and **register** (high vs. mid vs. low). The ear can follow all three simultaneously because they occupy different \"lanes\" in pitch-time space. This is how polyphony works at high density.

